# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: control-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] In control theory, a **bang–bang controller** (**hysteresis**, **2 step** or **on–off** controller), is a feedback controller that switches abruptly between two states.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] These controllers may be realized in terms of any element that provides hysteresis.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] They are often used to control a plant that accepts a binary input, for example a furnace that is either completely on or completely off.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Most common residential thermostats are bang–bang controllers.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] The Heaviside step function in its discrete form is an example of a **bang–bang control** signal.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Due to the discontinuous control signal, systems that include bang–bang controllers are variable structure systems, and bang–bang controllers are thus variable structure controllers.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] In optimal control problems, it is sometimes the case that a control is restricted to be between a lower and an upper bound.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] If the optimal control switches from one extreme to the other (i.e., is strictly never in between the bounds), then that control is referred to as a bang–bang solution.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Bang–bang controls frequently arise in minimum-time problems.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] For example, if it is desired for a car starting at rest to arrive at a certain position ahead of the car in the shortest possible time, the solution is to apply maximum acceleration until the unique *switching point*, and then apply maximum braking to come to rest exactly at the desired position.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] A familiar everyday example is bringing water to a boil in the shortest time, which is achieved by applying full heat, then turning it off when the water reaches a boil.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] A closed-loop household example is most thermostats, wherein the heating element or air conditioning compressor is either running or not, depending upon whether the measured temperature is above or below the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Bang–bang solutions also arise when the Hamiltonian is linear in the control variable; application of Pontryagin's minimum or maximum principle will then lead to pushing the control to its upper or lower bound depending on the sign of the coefficient of *u* in the Hamiltonian.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] In summary, bang–bang controls are actually *optimal* controls in some cases, although they are also often implemented because of simplicity or convenience.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Mathematically or within a computing context there may be no problems, but the physical realization of bang–bang control systems gives rise to several complications.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] First, depending on the width of the hysteresis gap and inertia in the process, there will be an oscillating error signal around the desired set point value (e.g., temperature), often saw-tooth shaped.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Room temperature may become uncomfortable just before the next switch 'ON' event.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Alternatively, a narrow hysteresis gap will lead to frequent on/off switching, which is often undesirable (e.g. an electrically ignited gas heater).
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Second, the onset of the step function may entail, for example, a high electrical current and/or sudden heating and expansion of metal vessels, ultimately leading to metal fatigue or other wear-and-tear effects.
[src:control-systems/bang-bang-control] Where possible, continuous control, such as in PID control, will avoid problems caused by the brisk state transitions that are the consequence of bang–bang control.
[src:control-systems/control-system] A **control system** manages, commands, directs, or regulates the behavior of other devices or systems using control loops.
[src:control-systems/control-system] It can range from a single home heating controller using a thermostat controlling a domestic boiler to large industrial control systems which are used for controlling processes or machines.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The control systems are designed via control engineering process.
[src:control-systems/control-system] For continuously modulated control, a feedback controller is used to automatically control a process or operation.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The control system compares the value or status of the process variable (PV) being controlled with the desired value or setpoint (SP), and applies the difference as a control signal to bring the process variable output of the plant to the same value as the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/control-system] For sequential and combinational logic, software logic, such as in a programmable logic controller, is used.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:control-systems/control-system] A closed-loop controller or feedback controller is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:control-systems/control-system] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:control-systems/control-system] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:control-systems/control-system] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:control-systems/control-system] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:control-systems/control-system] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:control-systems/control-system] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Logic control systems for industrial and commercial machinery were historically implemented by interconnected electrical relays and cam timers using ladder logic.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Today, most such systems are constructed with microcontrollers or more specialized programmable logic controllers (PLCs).
[src:control-systems/control-system] The notation of ladder logic is still in use as a programming method for PLCs.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Logic controllers may respond to switches and sensors and can cause the machinery to start and stop various operations through the use of actuators.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Logic controllers are used to sequence mechanical operations in many applications.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Examples include elevators, washing machines and other systems with interrelated operations.
[src:control-systems/control-system] An automatic sequential control system may trigger a series of mechanical actuators in the correct sequence to perform a task.
[src:control-systems/control-system] For example, various electric and pneumatic transducers may fold and glue a cardboard box, fill it with the product and then seal it in an automatic packaging machine.
[src:control-systems/control-system] PLC software can be written in many different ways – ladder diagrams, SFC (sequential function charts) or statement lists.
[src:control-systems/control-system] On–off control uses a feedback controller that switches abruptly between two states.
[src:control-systems/control-system] A simple bi-metallic domestic thermostat can be described as an on-off controller.
[src:control-systems/control-system] When the temperature in the room (PV) goes below the user setting (SP), the heater is switched on.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Another example is a pressure switch on an air compressor.
[src:control-systems/control-system] When the pressure (PV) drops below the setpoint (SP) the compressor is powered.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Refrigerators and vacuum pumps contain similar mechanisms.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Simple on–off control systems like these can be cheap and effective.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Linear control are control systems and control theory based on *negative feedback* for producing a control signal to maintain the controlled process variable (PV) at the desired setpoint (SP).
[src:control-systems/control-system] There are several types of linear control systems with different capabilities.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Fuzzy logic is an attempt to apply the easy design of logic controllers to the control of complex continuously varying systems.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Basically, a measurement in a fuzzy logic system can be partly true.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The rules of the system are written in natural language and translated into fuzzy logic.
[src:control-systems/control-system] For example, the design for a furnace would start with: "If the temperature is too high, reduce the fuel to the furnace.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Measurements from the real world (such as the temperature of a furnace) are *fuzzified* and logic is calculated arithmetic, as opposed to Boolean logic, and the outputs are *de-fuzzified* to control equipment.
[src:control-systems/control-system] When a robust fuzzy design is reduced to a single, quick calculation, it begins to resemble a conventional feedback loop solution and it might appear that the fuzzy design was unnecessary.
[src:control-systems/control-system] However, the fuzzy logic paradigm may provide scalability for large control systems where conventional methods become unwieldy or costly to derive.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Fuzzy electronics is an electronic technology that uses fuzzy logic instead of the two-value logic more commonly used in digital electronics.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The range of control system implementation is from compact controllers often with dedicated software for a particular machine or device, to distributed control systems for industrial process control for a large physical plant.
[src:control-systems/control-system] Logic systems and feedback controllers are usually implemented with programmable logic controllers.
[src:control-systems/control-system] The Broadly Reconfigurable and Expandable Automation Device (BREAD) is a recent framework that provides many open-source hardware devices which can be connected to create more complex data acquisition and control systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] To do this, a **controller** with the requisite corrective behavior is required.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This controller monitors the controlled process variable (PV), and compares it with the reference or set point (SP).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The difference between actual and desired value of the process variable, called the *error* signal, or SP-PV error, is applied as feedback to generate a control action to bring the controlled process variable to the same value as the set point.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Other aspects which are also studied are controllability and observability.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Control theory is used in control system engineering to design automation that have revolutionized manufacturing, aircraft, communications and other industries, and created new fields such as robotics.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Extensive use is usually made of a diagrammatic style known as the block diagram.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In it the transfer function, also known as the system function or network function, is a mathematical model of the relation between the input and output based on the differential equations describing the system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Control theory dates from the 19th century, when the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Control theory was further advanced by Edward Routh in 1874, Charles Sturm and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, who all contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria; and from 1922 onwards, the development of PID control theory by Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Although the most direct application of mathematical control theory is its use in control systems engineering (dealing with process control systems for robotics and industry), control theory is routinely applied to problems both the natural and behavioral sciences.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] As the general theory of feedback systems, control theory is useful wherever feedback occurs, making it important to fields like economics, operations research, and the life sciences.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Although control systems of various types date back to antiquity, a more formal analysis of the field began with a dynamics analysis of the centrifugal governor, conducted by the physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1868, entitled *On Governors*.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A centrifugal governor was already used to regulate the velocity of windmills.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Maxwell described and analyzed the phenomenon of self-oscillation, in which lags in the system may lead to overcompensation and unstable behavior.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This generated a flurry of interest in the topic, during which Maxwell's classmate, Edward John Routh, abstracted Maxwell's results for the general class of linear systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Independently, Adolf Hurwitz analyzed system stability using differential equations in 1877, resulting in what is now known as the Routh–Hurwitz theorem.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A notable application of dynamic control was in the area of crewed flight.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The Wright brothers made their first successful test flights on December 17, 1903, and were distinguished by their ability to control their flights for substantial periods (more so than the ability to produce lift from an airfoil, which was known).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Continuous, reliable control of the airplane was necessary for flights lasting longer than a few seconds.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] By World War II, control theory was becoming an important area of research.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control systems, and applied the bang-bang principle to the development of automatic flight control equipment for aircraft.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Other areas of application for discontinuous controls included fire-control systems, guidance systems and electronics.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Sometimes, mechanical methods are used to improve the stability of systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] For example, ship stabilizers are fins mounted beneath the waterline and emerging laterally.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In contemporary vessels, they may be gyroscopically controlled active fins, which have the capacity to change their angle of attack to counteract roll caused by wind or waves acting on the ship.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The Space Race also depended on accurate spacecraft control, and control theory has also seen an increasing use in fields such as economics and artificial intelligence.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Here, one might say that the goal is to find an internal model that obeys the good regulator theorem.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] So, for example, in economics, the more accurately a (stock or commodities) trading model represents the actions of the market, the more easily it can control that market (and extract "useful work" (profits) from it).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These last two examples take the narrow historical interpretation of control theory as a set of differential equations modeling and regulating kinetic motion, and broaden it into a vast generalization of a regulator interacting with a plant.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In contrast to the frequency-domain analysis of the classical control theory, modern control theory utilizes the time-domain state space representation, a mathematical model of a physical system as a set of input, output and state variables related by first-order differential equations.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] To abstract from the number of inputs, outputs, and states, the variables are expressed as vectors and the differential and algebraic equations are written in matrix form (the latter only being possible when the dynamical system is linear).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The state space representation (also known as the "time-domain approach") provides a convenient and compact way to model and analyze systems with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] With inputs and outputs, we would otherwise have to write down Laplace transforms to encode all the information about a system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Unlike the frequency domain approach, the use of the state-space representation is not limited to systems with linear components and zero initial conditions.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] "State space" refers to the space whose axes are the state variables.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The state of the system can be represented as a point within that space.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Control systems can be divided into different categories depending on the number of inputs and outputs.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The scope of classical control theory is limited to single-input and single-output (SISO) system design, except when analyzing for disturbance rejection using a second input.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The system analysis is carried out in the time domain using differential equations, in the complex-s domain with the Laplace transform, or in the frequency domain by transforming from the complex-s domain.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Many systems may be assumed to have a second order and single variable system response in the time domain.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A controller designed using classical theory often requires on-site tuning due to incorrect design approximations.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Yet, due to the easier physical implementation of classical controller designs as compared to systems designed using modern control theory, these controllers are preferred in most industrial applications.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The most common controllers designed using classical control theory are PID controllers.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A less common implementation may include either or both a Lead or Lag filter.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The ultimate end goal is to meet requirements typically provided in the time-domain called the step response, or at times in the frequency domain called the open-loop response.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The step response characteristics applied in a specification are typically percent overshoot, settling time, etc.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The open-loop response characteristics applied in a specification are typically Gain and Phase margin and bandwidth.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These characteristics may be evaluated through simulation including a dynamic model of the system under control coupled with the compensation model.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Modern control theory is carried out in the state space, and can deal with multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This overcomes the limitations of classical control theory in more sophisticated design problems, such as fighter aircraft control, with the limitation that no frequency domain analysis is possible.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In modern design, a system is represented to the greatest advantage as a set of decoupled first order differential equations defined using state variables.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Nonlinear, multivariable, adaptive and robust control theories come under this division.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Being fairly new, modern control theory has many areas yet to be explored.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Kálmán and Aleksandr Lyapunov are well known among the people who have shaped modern control theory.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The *stability* of a general dynamical system with no input can be described with Lyapunov stability criteria.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] For simplicity, the following descriptions focus on continuous-time and discrete-time **linear systems**.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Mathematically, this means that for a causal linear system to be stable all of the poles of its transfer function must have negative-real values, i.e. the real part of each pole must be less than zero.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The difference between the two cases is simply due to the traditional method of plotting continuous time versus discrete time transfer functions.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The continuous Laplace transform is in Cartesian coordinates where the x axis is the real axis and the discrete Z-transform is in circular coordinates where the $\rho$ axis is the real axis.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] When the appropriate conditions above are satisfied a system is said to be asymptotically stable; the variables of an asymptotically stable control system always decrease from their initial value and do not show permanent oscillations.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Permanent oscillations occur when a pole has a real part exactly equal to zero (in the continuous time case) or a modulus equal to one (in the discrete time case).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] If a simply stable system response neither decays nor grows over time, and has no oscillations, it is marginally stable; in this case the system transfer function has non-repeated poles at the complex plane origin (i.e. their real and complex component is zero in the continuous time case).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Oscillations are present when poles with real part equal to zero have an imaginary part not equal to zero.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] which has a pole in $z=0.5$ (zero imaginary part).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This system is BIBO (asymptotically) stable since the pole is *inside* the unit circle.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] which has a pole at $z=1.5$ and is not BIBO stable since the pole has a modulus strictly greater than one.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Numerous tools exist for the analysis of the poles of a system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These include graphical systems like the root locus, Bode plots or the Nyquist plots.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Mechanical changes can make equipment (and control systems) more stable.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Sailors add ballast to improve the stability of ships.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Cruise ships use antiroll fins that extend transversely from the side of the ship for perhaps 30 feet (10 m) and are continuously rotated about their axes to develop forces that oppose the roll.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Controllability and observability are main issues in the analysis of a system before deciding the best control strategy to be applied, or whether it is even possible to control or stabilize the system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Controllability is related to the possibility of forcing the system into a particular state by using an appropriate control signal.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, then no signal will ever be able to control the state.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, but its dynamics are stable, then the state is termed *stabilizable*.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Observability instead is related to the possibility of *observing*, through output measurements, the state of a system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] If a state is not observable, the controller will never be able to determine the behavior of an unobservable state and hence cannot use it to stabilize the system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] However, similar to the stabilizability condition above, if a state cannot be observed it might still be detectable.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] From a geometrical point of view, looking at the states of each variable of the system to be controlled, every "bad" state of these variables must be controllable and observable to ensure a good behavior in the closed-loop system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] That is, if one of the eigenvalues of the system is not both controllable and observable, this part of the dynamics will remain untouched in the closed-loop system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] If such an eigenvalue is not stable, the dynamics of this eigenvalue will be present in the closed-loop system which therefore will be unstable.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Unobservable poles are not present in the transfer function realization of a state-space representation, which is why sometimes the latter is preferred in dynamical systems analysis.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Solutions to problems of an uncontrollable or unobservable system include adding actuators and sensors.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Several different control strategies have been devised in the past years.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These vary from extremely general ones (PID controller), to others devoted to very particular classes of systems (especially robotics or aircraft cruise control).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A control problem can have several specifications.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Stability, of course, is always present.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The controller must ensure that the closed-loop system is stable, regardless of the open-loop stability.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A poor choice of controller can even worsen the stability of the open-loop system, which must normally be avoided.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Sometimes it would be desired to obtain particular dynamics in the closed loop: i.e. that the poles have $Re[\lambda ]<-{\overline {\lambda }}$ , where ${\overline {\lambda }}$ is a fixed value strictly greater than zero, instead of simply asking that $Re[\lambda ]<0$ .
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Another typical specification is the rejection of a step disturbance; including an integrator in the open-loop chain (i.e. directly before the system under control) easily achieves this.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Other classes of disturbances need different types of sub-systems to be included.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Other "classical" control theory specifications regard the time-response of the closed-loop system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These include the rise time (the time needed by the control system to reach the desired value after a perturbation), peak overshoot (the highest value reached by the response before reaching the desired value) and others (settling time, quarter-decay).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Frequency domain specifications are usually related to robustness (see after).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Modern performance assessments use some variation of integrated tracking error (IAE, ISA, CQI).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A control system must always have some robustness property.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A robust controller is such that its properties do not change much if applied to a system slightly different from the mathematical one used for its synthesis.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This requirement is important, as no real physical system truly behaves like the series of differential equations used to represent it mathematically.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Typically a simpler mathematical model is chosen in order to simplify calculations, otherwise, the true system dynamics can be so complicated that a complete model is impossible.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The process of determining the equations that govern the model's dynamics is called system identification.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This can be done off-line: for example, executing a series of measures from which to calculate an approximated mathematical model, typically its transfer function or matrix.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Such identification from the output, however, cannot take account of unobservable dynamics.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Sometimes the model is built directly starting from known physical equations, for example, in the case of a mass-spring-damper system we know that $m{\ddot {x}}(t)=-Kx(t)-\mathrm {B} {\dot {x}}(t)$ .
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Some advanced control techniques include an "on-line" identification process (see later).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The parameters of the model are calculated ("identified") while the controller itself is running.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In this way, if a drastic variation of the parameters ensues, for example, if the robot's arm releases a weight, the controller will adjust itself consequently in order to ensure the correct performance.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Analysis of the robustness of a SISO (single input single output) control system can be performed in the frequency domain, considering the system's transfer function and using Nyquist and Bode diagrams.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Topics include gain and phase margin and amplitude margin.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] For MIMO (multi-input multi output) and, in general, more complicated control systems, one must consider the theoretical results devised for each control technique (see next section).
[src:control-systems/control-theory] I.e., if particular robustness qualities are needed, the engineer must shift their attention to a control technique by including these qualities in its properties.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A particular robustness issue is the requirement for a control system to perform properly in the presence of input and state constraints.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In the physical world every signal is limited.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] It could happen that a controller will send control signals that cannot be followed by the physical system, for example, trying to rotate a valve at excessive speed.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] This can produce undesired behavior of the closed-loop system, or even damage or break actuators or other subsystems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Specific control techniques are available to solve the problem: model predictive control (see later), and anti-wind up systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The latter consists of an additional control block that ensures that the control signal never exceeds a given threshold.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] For MIMO systems, pole placement can be performed mathematically using a state space representation of the open-loop system and calculating a feedback matrix assigning poles in the desired positions.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In complicated systems this can require computer-assisted calculation capabilities, and cannot always ensure robustness.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Furthermore, all system states are not in general measured and so observers must be included and incorporated in pole placement design.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Processes in industries like robotics and the aerospace industry typically have strong nonlinear dynamics.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] In control theory it is sometimes possible to linearize such classes of systems and apply linear techniques, but in many cases it can be necessary to devise from scratch theories permitting control of nonlinear systems.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] These, e.g., feedback linearization, backstepping, sliding mode control, trajectory linearization control normally take advantage of results based on Lyapunov's theory.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Differential geometry has been widely used as a tool for generalizing well-known linear control concepts to the nonlinear case, as well as showing the subtleties that make it a more challenging problem.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Control theory has also been used to decipher the neural mechanism that directs cognitive states.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] When the system is controlled by multiple controllers, the problem is one of decentralized control.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Decentralization is helpful in many ways, for instance, it helps control systems to operate over a larger geographical area.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The agents in decentralized control systems can interact using communication channels and coordinate their actions.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A stochastic control problem is one in which the evolution of the state variables is subjected to random shocks from outside the system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] A deterministic control problem is not subject to external random shocks.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Every control system must guarantee first the stability of the closed-loop behavior.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] For linear systems, this can be obtained by directly placing the poles.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] Nonlinear control systems use specific theories (normally based on Aleksandr Lyapunov's Theory) to ensure stability without regard to the inner dynamics of the system.
[src:control-systems/control-theory] The possibility to fulfill different specifications varies from the model considered and the control strategy chosen.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Self-regulating mechanisms have existed since antiquity, and the idea of feedback started to enter economic theory in Britain by the 18th century, but it was not at that time recognized as a universal abstraction and so did not have a name.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The first ever known artificial feedback device was a float valve, for maintaining water at a constant level, invented in 270 BC in Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This device illustrated the principle of feedback: a low water level opens the valve, the rising water then provides feedback into the system, closing the valve when the required level is reached.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This then reoccurs in a circular fashion as the water level fluctuates.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Centrifugal governors were used to regulate the distance and pressure between millstones in windmills since the 17th century.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In 1788, James Watt designed his first centrifugal governor following a suggestion from his business partner Matthew Boulton, for use in the steam engines of their production.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Early steam engines employed a purely reciprocating motion, and were used for pumping water – an application that could tolerate variations in the working speed, but the use of steam engines for other applications called for more precise control of the speed.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In 1868, James Clerk Maxwell wrote a famous paper, "On governors", that is widely considered a classic in feedback control theory.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This was a landmark paper on control theory and the mathematics of feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] By the end of 1912, researchers using early electronic amplifiers (audions) had discovered that deliberately coupling part of the output signal back to the input circuit would boost the amplification (through regeneration), but would also cause the audion to howl or sing.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This action of feeding back of the signal from output to input gave rise to the use of the term "feedback" as a distinct word by 1920.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Increasing the feedback produced superregeneration.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The development of cybernetics from the 1940s onwards was centred around the study of circular causal feedback mechanisms.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Over the years there has been some dispute as to the best definition of feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] According to cybernetician Ashby (1956), mathematicians and theorists interested in the principles of feedback mechanisms prefer the definition of "circularity of action", which keeps the theory simple and consistent.
[src:control-systems/feedback] For those with more practical aims, feedback should be a deliberate effect via some more tangible connection.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Focusing on uses in management theory, Ramaprasad (1983) defines feedback generally as "...information about the gap between the actual level and the reference level of a system parameter" that is used to "alter the gap in some way".
[src:control-systems/feedback] He emphasizes that the information by itself is not feedback unless translated into action.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Positive feedback: If the signal feedback from output is in phase with the input signal, the feedback is called positive feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Negative feedback: If the signal feedback is out of phase by 180° with respect to the input signal, the feedback is called negative feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] As an example of negative feedback, the diagram might represent a cruise control system in a car that matches a target speed, such as the speed limit.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The controlled system is the car; its input includes the combined torque from the engine and from the changing slope of the road (the disturbance).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The car's speed (status) is measured by a speedometer.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The error signal is the difference between the speed as measured by the speedometer and the target speed (set point).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The controller interprets the speed to adjust the accelerator, commanding the fuel flow to the engine (the effector).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The resulting change in engine torque, the feedback, combines with the torque exerted by the change of road grade to reduce the error in speed, minimising the changing slope.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The terms "positive" and "negative" were first applied to feedback prior to WWII.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The idea of positive feedback already existed in the 1920s when the regenerative circuit was made.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Friis and Jensen (1924) described this circuit in a set of electronic amplifiers as a case where *the "feed-back" action is positive* in contrast to negative feed-back action, which they mentioned only in passing.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Harold Stephen Black's classic 1934 paper first details the use of negative feedback in electronic amplifiers.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Even before these terms were being used, James Clerk Maxwell had described their concept through several kinds of "component motions" associated with the centrifugal governors used in steam engines.
[src:control-systems/feedback] He distinguished those that lead to a continued *increase* in a disturbance or the amplitude of a wave or oscillation, from those that lead to a *decrease* of the same quality.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The terms positive and negative feedback are defined in different ways within different disciplines.
[src:control-systems/feedback] 2. the valence of the *action* or *effect* that alters the gap, based on whether it makes the recipient or observer *happy* (positive) or *unhappy* (negative).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The two definitions may be confusing, like when an incentive (reward) is used to boost poor performance (narrow a gap).
[src:control-systems/feedback] Referring to definition 1, some authors use alternative terms, replacing *positive* and *negative* with *self-reinforcing* and *self-correcting*, *reinforcing* and *balancing*, *discrepancy-enhancing* and *discrepancy-reducing* or *regenerative* and *degenerative* respectively.
[src:control-systems/feedback] And for definition 2, some authors promote describing the action or effect as *positive* and *negative* *reinforcement* or *punishment* rather than feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Yet even within a single discipline an example of feedback can be called either positive or negative, depending on how values are measured or referenced.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This confusion may arise because feedback can be used to provide *information* or *motivate*, and often has both a *qualitative* and a *quantitative* component.
[src:control-systems/feedback] While simple systems can sometimes be described as one or the other type, many systems with feedback loops cannot be shoehorned into either type, and this is especially true when multiple loops are present.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In general, feedback systems can have many signals fed back, and the feedback loops frequently contain mixtures of positive and negative feedback where positive and negative feedback can dominate at different frequencies or different points in the state space of a system.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The term bipolar feedback has been coined to refer to biological systems where positive and negative feedback systems can interact, the output of one affecting the input of another, and vice versa.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Some systems with feedback can have very complex behaviors, such as chaotic behaviors in non-linear systems, while others have much more predictable behaviors, such as those that are used to make and design digital systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback is used extensively in digital systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] For example, binary counters and similar devices employ feedback where the current state and inputs are used to calculate a new state, which is then fed back and clocked back into the device to update it.
[src:control-systems/feedback] By using feedback properties, the behavior of a system can be altered to meet the needs of an application; systems can be made stable, responsive or held constant.
[src:control-systems/feedback] It is shown that dynamical systems with a feedback experience an adaptation to the edge of chaos.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Physical systems present feedback through the mutual interactions of their parts.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback is also relevant for the regulation of experimental conditions, noise reduction, and signal control.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The thermodynamics of feedback-controlled systems has intrigued physicist since the Maxwell's demon, with recent advances on the consequences for entropy reduction and performance increase.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In biological systems such as organisms, ecosystems, or the biosphere, most parameters must stay under control within a narrow range around a certain optimal level under certain environmental conditions.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The deviation of the optimal value of the controlled parameter can result from changes in internal and external environments.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A change of some of the environmental conditions may also require a change of that range for the system to function.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The value of the parameter to maintain is recorded by a reception system and conveyed to a regulation module via an information channel.
[src:control-systems/feedback] An example of this is insulin oscillations.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Biological systems contain many types of regulatory circuits, both positive and negative.
[src:control-systems/feedback] As in other contexts, *positive* and *negative* do not imply that the feedback causes *good* or *bad* effects.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A negative feedback loop is one that tends to slow down a process, whereas a positive feedback loop tends to accelerate it.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The mirror neurons are part of a social feedback system, when an observed action is *mirrored* by the brain, like a self-performed action.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Normal tissue integrity is preserved by feedback interactions between diverse cell types mediated by adhesion molecules and secreted molecules that act as mediators; failure of key feedback mechanisms in cancer disrupts tissue function.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In an injured or infected tissue, inflammatory mediators elicit feedback responses in cells, which alter gene expression and change the groups of molecules expressed and secreted, including molecules that induce diverse cells to cooperate and restore tissue structure and function.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This type of feedback is important because it enables coordination of immune responses and recovery from infections and injuries.
[src:control-systems/feedback] During cancer, key elements of this feedback fail.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This disrupts tissue function and immunity.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Mechanisms of feedback were first elucidated in bacteria, where a nutrient elicits changes in some of their metabolic functions.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback is also central to the operations of genes and gene regulatory networks.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Repressor (see Lac repressor) and activator proteins are used to create genetic operons, which were identified by François Jacob and Jacques Monod in 1961 as *feedback loops*.
[src:control-systems/feedback] These feedback loops may be positive (as in the case of the coupling between a sugar molecule and the proteins that import sugar into a bacterial cell), or negative (as is often the case in metabolic consumption).
[src:control-systems/feedback] On a larger scale, feedback can have a stabilizing effect on animal populations even when profoundly affected by external changes, although time lags in feedback response can give rise to predator-prey cycles.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In zymology, feedback serves as regulation of activity of an enzyme by its direct product(s) or downstream metabolite(s) in the metabolic pathway (see Allosteric regulation).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis is largely controlled by positive and negative feedback, much of which is still unknown.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In psychology, the body receives a stimulus from the environment or internally that causes the release of hormones.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Release of hormones then may cause more of those hormones to be released, causing a positive feedback loop.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This cycle is also found in certain behaviour.
[src:control-systems/feedback] For example, "shame loops" occur in people who blush easily.
[src:control-systems/feedback] When they realize that they are blushing, they become even more embarrassed, which leads to further blushing, and so on.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The climate system is characterized by strong positive and negative feedback loops between processes that affect the state of the atmosphere, ocean, and land.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A simple example is the ice–albedo positive feedback loop whereby melting snow exposes more dark ground (of lower albedo), which in turn absorbs heat and causes more snow to melt.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback is extensively used in control theory, using a variety of methods including state space (controls), full state feedback, and so forth.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In the context of control theory, "feedback" is traditionally assumed to specify "negative feedback".
[src:control-systems/feedback] The most common general-purpose controller using a control-loop feedback mechanism is a proportional-integral-derivative (PID) controller.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Heuristically, the terms of a PID controller can be interpreted as corresponding to time: the proportional term depends on the *present* error, the integral term on the accumulation of *past* errors, and the derivative term is a prediction of *future* error, based on the current rate of change.
[src:control-systems/feedback] For feedback in the educational context, see corrective feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In ancient times, the float valve was used to regulate the flow of water in Greek and Roman water clocks; similar float valves are used to regulate fuel in a carburettor and also used to regulate tank water level in the flush toilet.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The Dutch inventor Cornelius Drebbel (1572–1633) built thermostats (c1620) to control the temperature of chicken incubators and chemical furnaces.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In 1745, the windmill was improved by blacksmith Edmund Lee, who added a fantail to keep the face of the windmill pointing into the wind.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In 1787, Tom Mead regulated the rotation speed of a windmill by using a centrifugal pendulum to adjust the distance between the bedstone and the runner stone (i.e., to adjust the load).
[src:control-systems/feedback] The use of the centrifugal governor by James Watt in 1788 to regulate the speed of his steam engine was one factor leading to the Industrial Revolution.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Steam engines also use float valves and pressure release valves as mechanical regulation devices.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A mathematical analysis of Watt's governor was done by James Clerk Maxwell in 1868.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The *Great Eastern* was one of the largest steamships of its time and employed a steam-powered rudder with a feedback mechanism designed in 1866 by John McFarlane Gray.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Joseph Farcot coined the word *servo* in 1873 to describe steam-powered steering systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Hydraulic servos were later used to position guns.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Elmer Ambrose Sperry of the Sperry Corporation designed the first autopilot in 1912.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Nicolas Minorsky published a theoretical analysis of automatic ship steering in 1922 and described the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Internal combustion engines of the late 20th century employed mechanical feedback mechanisms such as the vacuum timing advance but mechanical feedback was replaced by electronic engine management systems once small, robust and powerful single-chip microcontrollers became affordable.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The use of feedback is widespread in the design of electronic components such as amplifiers, oscillators, and stateful logic circuit elements such as flip-flops and counters.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Electronic feedback systems are also very commonly used to control mechanical, thermal and other physical processes.
[src:control-systems/feedback] If the signal is inverted on its way round the control loop, the system is said to have *negative feedback*; otherwise, the feedback is said to be *positive*.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Negative feedback is often deliberately introduced to increase the stability and accuracy of a system by correcting or reducing the influence of unwanted changes.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This scheme can fail if the input changes faster than the system can respond to it.
[src:control-systems/feedback] When this happens, the lag in arrival of the correcting signal can result in over-correction, causing the output to oscillate or "hunt".
[src:control-systems/feedback] While often an unwanted consequence of system behaviour, this effect is used deliberately in electronic oscillators.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Harry Nyquist at Bell Labs derived the Nyquist stability criterion for determining the stability of feedback systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] An easier method, but less general, is to use Bode plots developed by Hendrik Bode to determine the gain margin and phase margin.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Design to ensure stability often involves frequency compensation to control the location of the poles of the amplifier.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Electronic feedback loops are used to control the output of electronic devices, such as amplifiers.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A feedback loop is created when all or some portion of the output is fed back to the input.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A device is said to be operating *open loop* if no output feedback is being employed and *closed loop* if feedback is being used.
[src:control-systems/feedback] When two or more amplifiers are cross-coupled using positive feedback, complex behaviors can be created.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Negative feedback occurs when the fed-back output signal has a relative phase of 180° with respect to the input signal (upside down).
[src:control-systems/feedback] This situation is sometimes referred to as being *out of phase*, but that term is also used to indicate other phase separations, as in "90° out of phase".
[src:control-systems/feedback] Negative feedback can be used to correct output errors or to desensitize a system to unwanted fluctuations.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In feedback amplifiers, this correction is generally for waveform distortion reduction or to establish a specified gain level.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A general expression for the gain of a negative feedback amplifier is the asymptotic gain model.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Positive feedback occurs when the fed-back signal is in phase with the input signal.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Under certain gain conditions, positive feedback reinforces the input signal to the point where the output of the device oscillates between its maximum and minimum possible states.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Positive feedback may also introduce hysteresis into a circuit.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This can cause the circuit to ignore small signals and respond only to large ones.
[src:control-systems/feedback] It is sometimes used to eliminate noise from a digital signal.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Under some circumstances, positive feedback may cause a device to latch, i.e., to reach a condition in which the output is locked to its maximum or minimum state.
[src:control-systems/feedback] This fact is very widely used in digital electronics to make bistable circuits for volatile storage of information.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The loud squeals that sometimes occur in sound reinforcement, public address systems, and rock music are known as audio feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] If a microphone is in front of a loudspeaker that it is connected to, the sound that the microphone picks up comes out of the speaker, and is picked up by the microphone and re-amplified.
[src:control-systems/feedback] If the loop gain is sufficient, howling or squealing at the maximum power of the amplifier is possible.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The input signal is applied to the amplifier with open-loop gain *A* and amplified.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The output of the amplifier is applied to a feedback network with gain *B*, and subtracted from the input to the amplifier.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The loop gain is the product of all gains in the loop.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In the diagram shown, the loop gain is the product of the gains of the amplifier and the feedback network, *−AB*.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The minus sign is because the feedback signal is subtracted from the input.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The gains *A* and *B*, and therefore the loop gain, generally vary with the frequency of the input signal, and so are usually expressed as functions of the angular frequency *ω* in radians per second.
[src:control-systems/feedback] It is often displayed as a graph with the horizontal axis frequency *ω* and the vertical axis gain.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In amplifiers, the loop gain is the difference between the open-loop gain curve and the closed-loop gain curve (actually, the 1/B curve) on a dB scale.
[src:control-systems/feedback] An electronic oscillator is an electronic circuit that produces a periodic, oscillating electronic signal, often a sine wave or a square wave.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Oscillators convert direct current (DC) from a power supply to an alternating current signal.
[src:control-systems/feedback] They are widely used in many electronic devices.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Common examples of signals generated by oscillators include signals broadcast by radio and television transmitters, clock signals that regulate computers and quartz clocks, and the sounds produced by electronic beepers and video games.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Oscillators designed to produce a high-power AC output from a DC supply are usually called inverters.
[src:control-systems/feedback] There are two main types of electronic oscillator: the linear or harmonic oscillator and the nonlinear or relaxation oscillator.
[src:control-systems/feedback] A latch or a flip-flop is a circuit that has two stable states and can be used to store state information.
[src:control-systems/feedback] They typically constructed using feedback that crosses over between two arms of the circuit, to provide the circuit with a state.
[src:control-systems/feedback] The circuit can be made to change state by signals applied to one or more control inputs and will have one or two outputs.
[src:control-systems/feedback] It is the basic storage element in sequential logic.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Latches and flip-flops are fundamental building blocks of digital electronics systems used in computers, communications, and many other types of systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Latches and flip-flops are used as data storage elements.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Such data storage can be used for storage of *state*, and such a circuit is described as sequential logic.
[src:control-systems/feedback] When used in a finite-state machine, the output and next state depend not only on its current input, but also on its current state (and hence, previous inputs).
[src:control-systems/feedback] It can also be used for counting of pulses, and for synchronizing variably-timed input signals to some reference timing signal.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Flip-flops can be either simple (transparent or opaque) or clocked (synchronous or edge-triggered).
[src:control-systems/feedback] Although the term flip-flop has historically referred generically to both simple and clocked circuits, in modern usage it is common to reserve the term *flip-flop* exclusively for discussing clocked circuits; the simple ones are commonly called *latches*.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Using this terminology, a latch is level-sensitive, whereas a flip-flop is edge-sensitive.
[src:control-systems/feedback] That is, when a latch is enabled, it becomes transparent, while a flip flop's output only changes on a single type (positive going or negative going) of clock edge.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback loops provide generic mechanisms for controlling the running, maintenance, and evolution of software and computing systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback loops are important models in the engineering of adaptive software, as they define the behaviour of the interactions among the control elements over the adaptation process, to guarantee system properties at run-time.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback loops and foundations of control theory have been successfully applied to computing systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] In particular, they have been applied to the development of products such as IBM Db2 and IBM Tivoli.
[src:control-systems/feedback] From a software perspective, the autonomic (MAPE, monitor analyze plan execute) loop proposed by researchers of IBM is another valuable contribution to the application of feedback loops to the control of dynamic properties and the design and evolution of autonomic software systems.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Feedback is also a useful design principle for designing user interfaces.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Video feedback is the video equivalent of acoustic feedback.
[src:control-systems/feedback] It involves a loop between a video camera input and a video output, e.g., a television screen or monitor.
[src:control-systems/feedback] Aiming the camera at the display produces a complex video image based on the feedback.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The filter is constructed as a mean squared error minimiser, but an alternative derivation of the filter is also provided showing how the filter relates to maximum likelihood statistics.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has numerous technological applications.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] A common application is for guidance, navigation, and control of vehicles, particularly aircraft, spacecraft and ships positioned dynamically.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Furthermore, Kalman filtering is much applied in time series analysis tasks such as signal processing and econometrics.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is also important for robotic motion planning and control, and can be used for trajectory optimization.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering also works for modeling the central nervous system's control of movement.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Due to the time delay between issuing motor commands and receiving sensory feedback, the use of Kalman filters provides a realistic model for making estimates of the current state of a motor system and issuing updated commands.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm works via a two-phase process: a *prediction phase* and an *update phase*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the Kalman filter produces estimates of the current state variables, including their uncertainties.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Once the outcome of the next measurement (necessarily corrupted with some error, including random noise) is observed, these estimates are updated using a weighted average, with more weight given to estimates with greater certainty.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It can operate in real time, using only the present input measurements and the state calculated previously and its uncertainty matrix; no additional past information is required.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Optimality of Kalman filtering assumes that errors have a normal (Gaussian) distribution.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, "The following assumptions are made about random processes: Physical random phenomena may be thought of as due to primary random sources exciting dynamic systems.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It is a common misconception (perpetuated in the literature) that the Kalman filter cannot be rigorously applied unless all noise processes are assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Extensions and generalizations of the method have also been developed, such as the extended Kalman filter and the unscented Kalman filter which work on nonlinear systems.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The basis is a hidden Markov model such that the state space of the latent variables is continuous and all latent and observed variables have Gaussian distributions.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has been used successfully in multi-sensor fusion, and distributed sensor networks to develop distributed or consensus Kalman filtering.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The filtering method is named for Hungarian émigré Rudolf E.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, although Thorvald Nicolai Thiele and Peter Swerling developed a similar algorithm earlier.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Bucy of the Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory contributed to the theory, causing it to be known sometimes as Kalman–Bucy filtering.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman was inspired to derive the Kalman filter by applying state variables to the Wiener filtering problem.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Schmidt is generally credited with developing the first implementation of a Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] He realized that the filter could be divided into two distinct parts, with one part for time periods between sensor outputs and another part for incorporating measurements.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It was during a visit by Kálmán to the NASA Ames Research Center that Schmidt saw the applicability of Kálmán's ideas to the nonlinear problem of trajectory estimation for the Apollo program resulting in its incorporation in the Apollo navigation computer.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This digital filter is sometimes termed the *Stratonovich–Kalman–Bucy filter* because it is a special case of a more general, nonlinear filter developed by the Soviet mathematician Ruslan Stratonovich.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, some of the special case linear filter's equations appeared in papers by Stratonovich that were published before the summer of 1961, when Kalman met with Stratonovich during a conference in Moscow.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This Kalman filtering was first described and developed partially in technical papers by Swerling (1958), Kalman (1960) and Kalman and Bucy (1961).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filters have been vital in the implementation of the navigation systems of U.S.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Navy nuclear ballistic missile submarines, and in the guidance and navigation systems of cruise missiles such as the U.S.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Air Force's Air Launched Cruise Missile.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] They are also used in the guidance and navigation systems of reusable launch vehicles and the attitude control and navigation systems of spacecraft which dock at the International Space Station.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] As such, it is a common sensor fusion and data fusion algorithm.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Noisy sensor data, approximations in the equations that describe the system evolution, and external factors that are not accounted for, all limit how well it is possible to determine the system's state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter deals effectively with the uncertainty due to noisy sensor data and, to some extent, with random external factors.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter produces an estimate of the state of the system as an average of the system's predicted state and of the new measurement using a weighted average.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The purpose of the weights is that values with better (i.e., smaller) estimated uncertainty are "trusted" more.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The weights are calculated from the covariance, a measure of the estimated uncertainty of the prediction of the system's state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The result of the weighted average is a new state estimate that lies between the predicted and measured state, and has a better estimated uncertainty than either alone.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This process is repeated at every time step, with the new estimate and its covariance informing the prediction used in the following iteration.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This means that Kalman filter works recursively and requires only the last "best guess", rather than the entire history, of a system's state to calculate a new state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The measurements' certainty-grading and current-state estimate are important considerations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It is common to discuss the filter's response in terms of the Kalman filter's *gain*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman gain is the weight given to the measurements and current-state estimate, and can be "tuned" to achieve a particular performance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] With a high gain, the filter places more weight on the most recent measurements, and thus conforms to them more responsively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] With a low gain, the filter conforms to the model predictions more closely.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] At the extremes, a high gain (close to one) will result in a more jumpy estimated trajectory, while a low gain (close to zero) will smooth out noise but decrease the responsiveness.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] When performing the actual calculations for the filter (as discussed below), the state estimate and covariances are coded into matrices because of the multiple dimensions involved in a single set of calculations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This allows for a representation of linear relationships between different state variables (such as position, velocity, and acceleration) in any of the transition models or covariances.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] As an example application, consider the problem of determining the precise location of a truck.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The truck can be equipped with a GPS unit that provides an estimate of the position within a few meters.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The GPS estimate is likely to be noisy; readings 'jump around' rapidly, though remaining within a few meters of the real position.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In addition, since the truck is expected to follow the laws of physics, its position can also be estimated by integrating its velocity over time, determined by keeping track of wheel revolutions and the angle of the steering wheel.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This is a technique known as dead reckoning.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the dead reckoning will provide a very smooth estimate of the truck's position, but it will drift over time as small errors accumulate.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] For this example, the Kalman filter can be thought of as operating in two distinct phases: predict and update.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the truck's old position will be modified according to the physical laws of motion (the dynamic or "state transition" model).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Not only will a new position estimate be calculated, but also a new covariance will be calculated as well.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Perhaps the covariance is proportional to the speed of the truck because we are more uncertain about the accuracy of the dead reckoning position estimate at high speeds but very certain about the position estimate at low speeds.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Next, in the update phase, a measurement of the truck's position is taken from the GPS unit.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Along with this measurement comes some amount of uncertainty, and its covariance relative to that of the prediction from the previous phase determines how much the new measurement will affect the updated prediction.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Ideally, as the dead reckoning estimates tend to drift away from the real position, the GPS measurement should pull the position estimate back toward the real position but not disturb it to the point of becoming noisy and rapidly jumping.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is an efficient recursive filter estimating the internal state of a linear dynamic system from a series of noisy measurements.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It is used in a wide range of engineering and econometric applications from radar and computer vision to estimation of structural macroeconomic models, and is an important topic in control theory and control systems engineering.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Together with the linear-quadratic regulator (LQR), the Kalman filter solves the linear–quadratic–Gaussian control problem (LQG).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter, the linear-quadratic regulator, and the linear–quadratic–Gaussian controller are solutions to what arguably are the most fundamental problems of control theory.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In most applications, the internal state is much larger (has more degrees of freedom) than the few "observable" parameters which are measured.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] However, by combining a series of measurements, the Kalman filter can estimate the entire internal state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] For the Dempster–Shafer theory, each state equation or observation is considered a special case of a linear belief function and the Kalman filtering is a special case of combining linear belief functions on a join-tree or Markov tree.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Additional methods include belief filtering which use Bayes or evidential updates to the state equations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] A wide variety of Kalman filters exists by now: Kalman's original formulation - now termed the "simple" Kalman filter, the Kalman–Bucy filter, Schmidt's "extended" filter, the information filter, and a variety of "square-root" filters that were developed by Bierman, Thornton, and many others.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is based on linear dynamic systems discretized in the time domain.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] They are modeled on a Markov chain built on linear operators perturbed by errors that may include Gaussian noise.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The state of the target system refers to the ground truth (yet hidden) system configuration of interest, which is represented as a vector of real numbers.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] At each discrete time increment, a linear operator is applied to the state to generate the new state, with some noise mixed in, and optionally some information from the controls on the system if they are known.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Then, another linear operator mixed with more noise generates the measurable outputs (i.e., observation) from the true ("hidden") state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter may be regarded as analogous to the hidden Markov model, with the difference that the hidden state variables have values in a continuous space as opposed to a discrete state space as for the hidden Markov model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] There is a strong analogy between the equations of a Kalman Filter and those of the hidden Markov model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] A review of this and other models is given in Roweis and Ghahramani (1999) and Hamilton (1994), Chapter 13.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In order to use the Kalman filter to estimate the internal state of a process given only a sequence of noisy observations, one must model the process in accordance with the following framework.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] As seen below, it is common in many applications that the matrices $\mathbf {F}$ , $\mathbf {H}$ , $\mathbf {Q}$ , $\mathbf {R}$ , and $\mathbf {B}$ are constant across time, in which case their k index may be dropped.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If $\mathbf {Q}$ is independent of time, one may, following Roweis and Ghahramani, write $\mathbf {w} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ to emphasize that the noise has no explicit knowledge of time.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Analogously to the situation for $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ , one may write $\mathbf {v} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ if $\mathbf {R}$ is independent of time.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The initial state, and the noise vectors at each step $\{\mathbf {x} _{0},\mathbf {w} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {w} _{k},\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}\}$ are all assumed to be mutually independent.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Many real-time dynamic systems do not exactly conform to this model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, unmodeled dynamics can seriously degrade the filter performance, even when it was supposed to work with unknown stochastic signals as inputs.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The reason for this is that the effect of unmodeled dynamics depends on the input, and, therefore, can bring the estimation algorithm to instability (it diverges).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] On the other hand, independent white noise signals will not make the algorithm diverge.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The problem of distinguishing between measurement noise and unmodeled dynamics is a difficult one and is treated as a problem of control theory using robust control.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a recursive estimator.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This means that only the estimated state from the previous time step and the current measurement are needed to compute the estimate for the current state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In contrast to batch estimation techniques, no history of observations and/or estimates is required.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In what follows, the notation ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{n\mid m}$ represents the estimate of $\mathbf {x}$ at time *n* given observations up to and including at time *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm structure of the Kalman filter resembles that of Alpha beta filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be written as a single equation; however, it is most often conceptualized as two distinct phases: "Predict" and "Update".
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The predict phase uses the state estimate from the previous timestep to produce an estimate of the state at the current timestep.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This predicted state estimate is also known as the *a priori* state estimate because, although it is an estimate of the state at the current timestep, it does not include observation information from the current timestep.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In the update phase, the innovation (the pre-fit residual), i.e. the difference between the current *a priori* prediction and the current observation information, is multiplied by the optimal Kalman gain and combined with the previous state estimate to refine the state estimate.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This improved estimate based on the current observation is termed the *a posteriori* state estimate.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the two phases alternate, with the prediction advancing the state until the next scheduled observation, and the update incorporating the observation.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] However, this is not necessary; if an observation is unavailable for some reason, the update may be skipped and multiple prediction procedures performed.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Likewise, if multiple independent observations are available at the same time, multiple update procedures may be performed (typically with different observation matrices **H***k*).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The second formula for the updated (*a posteriori*) estimate covariance above is known as the "Joseph form" that is often used in applications (numerically more stable than the more simple usual formulation).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Proof of the formulae is found in the *derivations* section, where the formula valid for any **K**k is also shown.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This expression reminds us of a linear interpolation, $x=(1-t)(a)+t(b)$ for t between [0,1].
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This expression also resembles the alpha beta filter update step.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] where $\operatorname {E} [\xi ]$ is the expected value of $\xi$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] That is, all estimates have a mean error of zero.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] so covariance matrices accurately reflect the covariance of estimates.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Practical implementation of a Kalman Filter is often difficult due to the difficulty of getting a good estimate of the noise covariance matrices **Q***k* and **R***k*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Extensive research has been done to estimate these covariances from data.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] One practical method of doing this is the *autocovariance least-squares* (ALS) technique that uses the time-lagged autocovariances of routine operating data to estimate the covariances.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The GNU Octave and Matlab code used to calculate the noise covariance matrices using the ALS technique is available online using the GNU General Public License.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Another approach is the *Optimized Kalman Filter* (OKF), which considers the covariance matrices not as representatives of the noise, but rather, as parameters aimed to achieve the most accurate state estimation.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] These two views coincide under the KF assumptions, but often contradict each other in real systems.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, OKF's state estimation is more robust to modeling inaccuracies.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter provides an optimal state estimation in cases where a) the model matches the real system perfectly, b) the entering noise is "white" (uncorrelated), and c) the covariances of the noise are known exactly.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Correlated noise can also be treated using Kalman filters.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Several methods for the noise covariance estimation have been proposed during past decades, including ALS, mentioned in the section above.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] More generally, if the model assumptions do not match the real system perfectly, then optimal state estimation is not necessarily obtained by setting **Q***k* and **R***k* to the covariances of the noise.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Instead, in that case, the parameters **Q***k* and **R***k* may be set to explicitly optimize the state estimation, e.g., using standard supervised learning.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] After the covariances are set, it is useful to evaluate the performance of the filter; i.e., whether it is possible to improve the state estimation quality.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If the Kalman filter works optimally, the innovation sequence (the output prediction error) is a white noise, therefore the whiteness property of the innovations measures filter performance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Several different methods can be used for this purpose.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If the noise terms are distributed in a non-Gaussian manner, methods for assessing performance of the filter estimate, which use probability inequalities or large-sample theory, are known in the literature.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Consider a truck on frictionless, straight rails.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Initially, the truck is stationary at position 0, but it is buffeted this way and that by random uncontrolled forces.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] We measure the position of the truck every Δ*t* seconds, but these measurements are imprecise; we want to maintain a model of the truck's position and velocity.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] We show here how we derive the model from which we create our Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Since $\mathbf {F} ,\mathbf {H} ,\mathbf {R} ,\mathbf {Q}$ are constant, their time indices are dropped.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] where ${\dot {x}}$ is the velocity, that is, the derivative of position with respect to time.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] We assume that between the (*k* − 1) and *k* timestep, uncontrolled forces cause a constant acceleration of *a**k* that is normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**a*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] (there is no $\mathbf {B} u$ term since there are no known control inputs.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ is not full rank (it is of rank one if $\Delta t\neq 0$ ).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Hence, the distribution $N(0,\mathbf {Q} )$ is not absolutely continuous and has no probability density function.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] At each time phase, a noisy measurement of the true position of the truck is made.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Let us suppose the measurement noise *v**k* is also distributed normally, with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**z*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The filter will then prefer the information from the first measurements over the information already in the model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] For simplicity, assume that the control input $\mathbf {u} _{k}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] A similar equation holds if we include a non-zero control input.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ and covariance matrices $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ evolve independently of the measurements $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Since these depend only on the model, and not the measurements, they may be computed offline.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Convergence of the gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ to an asymptotic matrix $\mathbf {K} _{\infty }$ applies for conditions established in Walrand and Dimakis.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If the $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ series converges, then it converges exponentially to an asymptotic $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ , assuming non-zero plant noise.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Recent analysis has shown that the *rate and nature* of this convergence can involve multiple coequal modes, including oscillatory components, depending on the eigenstructure of the Jacobian of the above Riccati map evaluated at $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] For the moving truck example described above, with $\Delta t=1$ and $\sigma _{a}^{2}=\sigma _{z}^{2}=\sigma _{x}^{2}=\sigma _{\dot {x}}^{2}=1$ , simulation shows convergence in $10$ iterations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The asymptotic gain is then computed as before.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be derived as a generalized least squares method operating on previous data.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This formula (sometimes known as the **Joseph form** of the covariance update equation) is valid for any value of **K***k*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It turns out that if **K***k* is the optimal Kalman gain, this can be simplified further as shown below.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a minimum mean-square error (MMSE) estimator.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] We seek to minimize the expected value of the square of the magnitude of this vector, $\operatorname {E} \left[\left\|\mathbf {x} _{k}-{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k|k}\right\|^{2}\right]$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This is equivalent to minimizing the trace of the *a posteriori* estimate covariance matrix $\mathbf {P} _{k|k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The trace is minimized when its matrix derivative with respect to the gain matrix is zero.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This gain, which is known as the *optimal Kalman gain*, is the one that yields MMSE estimates when used.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The formula used to calculate the *a posteriori* error covariance can be simplified when the Kalman gain equals the optimal value derived above.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This formula is computationally cheaper and thus nearly always used in practice, but is only correct for the optimal gain.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If arithmetic precision is unusually low causing problems with numerical stability, or if a non-optimal Kalman gain is deliberately used, this simplification cannot be applied; the *a posteriori* error covariance formula as derived above (Joseph form) must be used.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filtering equations provide an estimate of the state ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and its error covariance $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ recursively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The estimate and its quality depend on the system parameters and the noise statistics fed as inputs to the estimator.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This section analyzes the effect of uncertainties in the statistical inputs to the filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] no longer provides the actual error covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] In most real-time applications, the covariance matrices that are used in designing the Kalman filter are different from the actual (true) noise covariances matrices.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This sensitivity analysis describes the behavior of the estimation error covariance when the noise covariances as well as the system matrices $\mathbf {F} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {H} _{k}$ that are fed as inputs to the filter are incorrect.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, the sensitivity analysis describes the robustness (or sensitivity) of the estimator to misspecified statistical and parametric inputs to the estimator.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This discussion is limited to the error sensitivity analysis for the case of statistical uncertainties.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Here the actual noise covariances are denoted by $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ respectively, whereas the design values used in the estimator are $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The actual error covariance is denoted by $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ as computed by the Kalman filter is referred to as the Riccati variable.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The recursive expressions for $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are identical except for the presence of $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ in place of the design values $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Researches have been done to analyze Kalman filter system's robustness.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] One problem with the Kalman filter is its numerical stability.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] If the process noise covariance **Q***k* is small, round-off error often causes a small positive eigenvalue of the state covariance matrix **P** to be computed as a negative number.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This renders the numerical representation of **P** indefinite, while its true form is positive-definite.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Positive definite matrices have the property that they have a factorization into the product of a non-singular, lower-triangular matrix **S** and its transpose : **P** = **S**·**S**T .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The factor **S** can be computed efficiently using the Cholesky factorization algorithm.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This product form of the covariance matrix **P** is guaranteed to be symmetric, and for all 1 <= k <= n, the k-th diagonal element **P**kk is equal to the square of the euclidean norm of the k-th row of **S**, which is necessarily positive.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Between the two, the U-D factorization uses the same amount of storage, and somewhat less computation, and is the most commonly used triangular factorization.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Efficient algorithms for the Kalman prediction and update steps in the factored form were developed by G.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The **L**·**D**·**L**T decomposition of the innovation covariance matrix **S**k is the basis for another type of numerically efficient and robust square root filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm starts with the LU decomposition as implemented in the Linear Algebra PACKage (LAPACK).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] These results are further factored into the **L**·**D**·**L**T structure with methods given by Golub and Van Loan (algorithm 4.1.2) for a symmetric nonsingular matrix.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] Any singular covariance matrix is pivoted so that the first diagonal partition is nonsingular and well-conditioned.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The pivoting algorithm must retain any portion of the innovation covariance matrix directly corresponding to observed state-variables **H**k·**x**k|k-1 that are associated with auxiliary observations in **y**k.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The **l**·**d**·**l**t square-root filter requires orthogonalization of the observation vector.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This may be done with the inverse square-root of the covariance matrix for the auxiliary variables using Method 2 in Higham (2002, p.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is efficient for sequential data processing on central processing units (CPUs), but in its original form it is inefficient on parallel architectures such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] It is however possible to express the filter-update routine in terms of an associative operator using the formulation in Särkkä and García-Fernández (2021).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] The filter solution can then be retrieved by the use of a prefix sum algorithm which can be efficiently implemented on GPU.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p01] This reduces the computational complexity from $O(N)$ in the number of time steps to $O(\log(N))$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter can be presented as one of the simplest dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter calculates estimates of the true values of states recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, recursive Bayesian estimation calculates estimates of an unknown probability density function (PDF) recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In recursive Bayesian estimation, the true state is assumed to be an unobserved Markov process, and the measurements are the observed states of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Because of the Markov assumption, the true state is conditionally independent of all earlier states given the immediately previous state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, the measurement at the *k*-th timestep is dependent only upon the current state and is conditionally independent of all other states given the current state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] However, when a Kalman filter is used to estimate the state **x**, the probability distribution of interest is that associated with the current states conditioned on the measurements up to the current timestep.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This is achieved by marginalizing out the previous states and dividing by the probability of the measurement set.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This results in the *predict* and *update* phases of the Kalman filter written probabilistically.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The probability distribution of the update is proportional to the product of the measurement likelihood and the predicted state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The PDF at the previous timestep is assumed inductively to be the estimated state and covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This is justified because, as an optimal estimator, the Kalman filter makes best use of the measurements, therefore the PDF for $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ given the measurements $\mathbf {Z} _{k}$ is the Kalman filter estimate.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Related to the recursive Bayesian interpretation described above, the Kalman filter can be viewed as a generative model, i.e., a process for *generating* a stream of random observations **z** = (**z**0, **z**1, **z**2, ...).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This process has identical structure to the hidden Markov model, except that the discrete state and observations are replaced with continuous variables sampled from Gaussian distributions.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In some applications, it is useful to compute the *probability* that a Kalman filter with a given set of parameters (prior distribution, transition and observation models, and control inputs) would generate a particular observed signal.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This probability is known as the marginal likelihood because it integrates over ("marginalizes out") the values of the hidden state variables, so it can be computed using only the observed signal.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The marginal likelihood can be useful to evaluate different parameter choices, or to compare the Kalman filter against other models using Bayesian model comparison.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] It is straightforward to compute the marginal likelihood as a side effect of the recursive filtering computation.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] i.e., a product of Gaussian densities, each corresponding to the density of one observation **z***k* under the current filtering distribution $\mathbf {H} _{k}{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1},\mathbf {S} _{k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This can easily be computed as a simple recursive update; however, to avoid numeric underflow, in a practical implementation it is usually desirable to compute the *log* marginal likelihood $\ell =\log p(\mathbf {z} )$ instead.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] where $d_{y}$ is the dimension of the measurement vector.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] An important application where such a (log) likelihood of the observations (given the filter parameters) is used is multi-target tracking.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] For example, consider an object tracking scenario where a stream of observations is the input, however, it is unknown how many objects are in the scene (or, the number of objects is known but is greater than one).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] For such a scenario, it can be unknown apriori which observations/measurements were generated by which object.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] A multiple hypothesis tracker (MHT) typically will form different track association hypotheses, where each hypothesis can be considered as a Kalman filter (for the linear Gaussian case) with a specific set of parameters associated with the hypothesized object.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Thus, it is important to compute the likelihood of the observations for the different hypotheses under consideration, such that the most-likely one can be found.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Additionally, the information filter allows for system information initialization according to ${I_{1|0}=P_{1|0}^{-1}=0}$ , which would not be possible for the regular Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In the information filter, or inverse covariance filter, the estimated covariance and estimated state are replaced by the information matrix and information vector respectively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The information update now becomes a trivial sum.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The main advantage of the information filter is that *N* measurements can be filtered at each time step simply by summing their information matrices and vectors.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] To predict the information filter the information matrix and vector can be converted back to their state space equivalents, or alternatively the information space prediction can be used.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-lag smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-N\mid k}$ for a given fixed-lag N using the measurements from $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-interval smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ ( $k<n$ ) using the measurements from a fixed interval $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] There are several smoothing algorithms in common use.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The Rauch–Tung–Striebel (RTS) smoother is an efficient two-pass algorithm for fixed interval smoothing.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The forward pass is the same as the regular Kalman filter algorithm.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] These *filtered* a-priori and a-posteriori state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1}$ , ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k-1}$ , $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are saved for use in the backward pass (for retrodiction).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In the backward pass, we compute the *smoothed* state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}$ is the a-posteriori state estimate of timestep k and $\mathbf {x} _{k+1\mid k}$ is the a-priori state estimate of timestep $k+1$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The same notation applies to the covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] An alternative to the RTS algorithm is the modified Bryson–Frazier (MBF) fixed interval smoother developed by Bierman.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This also uses a backward pass that processes data saved from the Kalman filter forward pass.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The equations for the backward pass involve the recursive computation of data which are used at each observation time to compute the smoothed state and covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] An important advantage of the MBF is that it does not require finding the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Bierman's derivation is based on the RTS smoother, which assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] However, a derivation of the MBF based on the concept of the fixed point smoother, which does not require the Gaussian assumption, is given by Gibbs.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The MBF can also be used to perform consistency checks on the filter residuals and the difference between the value of a filter state after an update and the smoothed value of the state, that is $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}-\mathbf {x} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The minimum-variance smoother can attain the best-possible error performance, provided that the models are linear, their parameters and the noise statistics are known precisely.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This smoother is a time-varying state-space generalization of the optimal non-causal Wiener filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The smoother calculations are done in two passes.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The above system is known as the inverse Wiener-Hopf factor.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The backward recursion is the adjoint of the above forward system.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The result of the backward pass $\beta _{k}$ may be calculated by operating the forward equations on the time-reversed $\alpha _{k}$ and time reversing the result.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] which is identical to the minimum-variance Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The above solutions minimize the variance of the output estimation error.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Note that the Rauch–Tung–Striebel smoother derivation assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian, whereas the minimum-variance solutions do not.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Optimal smoothers for state estimation and input estimation can be constructed similarly.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] A continuous-time version of the above smoother is described in.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Expectation–maximization algorithms may be employed to calculate approximate maximum likelihood estimates of unknown state-space parameters within minimum-variance filters and smoothers.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Often uncertainties remain within problem assumptions.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] A smoother that accommodates uncertainties can be designed by adding a positive definite term to the Riccati equation.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In cases where the models are nonlinear, step-wise linearizations may be within the minimum-variance filter and smoother recursions (extended Kalman filtering).
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Pioneering research on the perception of sounds at different frequencies was conducted by Fletcher and Munson in the 1930s.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Their work led to a standard way of weighting measured sound levels within investigations of industrial noise and hearing loss.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Frequency weightings have since been used within filter and controller designs to manage performance within bands of interest.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, a frequency shaping function is used to weight the average power of the error spectral density in a specified frequency band.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Let $\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ denote the output estimation error exhibited by a conventional Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Also, let $\mathbf {W}$ denote a causal frequency weighting transfer function.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The optimum solution which minimizes the variance of $\mathbf {W} \left(\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}\right)$ arises by simply constructing $\mathbf {W} ^{-1}{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The design of $\mathbf {W}$ remains an open question.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] One way of proceeding is to identify a system which generates the estimation error and setting $\mathbf {W}$ equal to the inverse of that system.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This procedure may be iterated to obtain mean-square error improvement at the cost of increased filter order.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The same technique can be applied to smoothers.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The basic Kalman filter is limited to a linear assumption.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] More complex systems, however, can be nonlinear.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The nonlinearity can be associated either with the process model or with the observation model or with both.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The most common variants of Kalman filters for non-linear systems are the Extended Kalman Filter and Unscented Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The suitability of which filter to use depends on the non-linearity indices of the process and observation model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] In the extended Kalman filter (EKF), the state transition and observation models need not be linear functions of the state but may instead be nonlinear functions.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] These functions are of differentiable type.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The function *f* can be used to compute the predicted state from the previous estimate and similarly the function *h* can be used to compute the predicted measurement from the predicted state.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] However, *f* and *h* cannot be applied to the covariance directly.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Instead a matrix of partial derivatives (the Jacobian) is computed.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] At each timestep the Jacobian is evaluated with current predicted states.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] These matrices can be used in the Kalman filter equations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This process essentially linearizes the nonlinear function around the current estimate.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] When the state transition and observation models—that is, the predict and update functions f and h —are highly nonlinear, the extended Kalman filter can give particularly poor performance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This is because the covariance is propagated through linearization of the underlying nonlinear model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The unscented Kalman filter (UKF) uses a deterministic sampling technique known as the unscented transformation (UT) to pick a minimal set of sample points (called sigma points) around the mean.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are then propagated through the nonlinear functions, from which a new mean and covariance estimate are formed.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The resulting filter depends on how the transformed statistics of the UT are calculated and which set of sigma points are used.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] It should be remarked that it is always possible to construct new UKFs in a consistent way.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] For certain systems, the resulting UKF more accurately estimates the true mean and covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This can be verified with Monte Carlo sampling or Taylor series expansion of the posterior statistics.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, $\mathbf {A}$ is obtained via Cholesky decomposition of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] With some care the filter equations can be expressed in such a way that $\mathbf {A}$ is evaluated directly without intermediate calculations of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This is referred to as the *square-root unscented Kalman filter*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The weight of the mean value, $W_{0}$ , can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] $\alpha$ and $\kappa$ control the spread of the sigma points. $\beta$ is related to the distribution of x .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Note that this is an overparameterization in the sense that any one of $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\kappa$ can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Appropriate values depend on the problem at hand, but a typical recommendation is $\alpha =1$ , $\beta =0$ , and $\kappa \approx 3L/2$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] If the true distribution of x is Gaussian, $\beta =2$ is optimal.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] As with the EKF, the UKF prediction can be used independently from the UKF update, in combination with a linear (or indeed EKF) update, or vice versa.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Given estimates of the mean and covariance, ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-1\mid k-1}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ , one obtains $N=2L+1$ sigma points as described in the section above.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are propagated through the transition function *f*.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The propagated sigma points are weighed to produce the predicted mean and covariance.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] where $W_{j}^{a}$ are the first-order weights of the original sigma points, and $W_{j}^{c}$ are the second-order weights.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The matrix $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ is the covariance of the transition noise, $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] These sigma points are transformed through the measurement function h .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Then the empirical mean and covariance of the transformed points are calculated.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ is the covariance matrix of the observation noise, $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] This replaces the generative specification of the standard Kalman filter with a discriminative model for the latent states given observations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Such an approach proves particularly useful when the dimensionality of the observations is much greater than that of the latent states and can be used to build filters that are particularly robust to nonstationarities in the observation model.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Adaptive Kalman filters allow to adapt for process dynamics which are not modeled in the process model $\mathbf {F} (t)$ , which happens for example in the context of a maneuvering target when a constant velocity (reduced order) Kalman filter is employed for tracking.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Kalman–Bucy filtering (named for Richard Snowden Bucy) is a continuous time version of Kalman filtering.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {Q} (t)$ and $\mathbf {R} (t)$ represent the intensities of the two white noise terms $\mathbf {w} (t)$ and $\mathbf {v} (t)$ , respectively.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The distinction between the prediction and update steps of discrete-time Kalman filtering does not exist in continuous time.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The second differential equation, for the covariance, is an example of a Riccati equation.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Nonlinear generalizations to Kalman–Bucy filters include continuous time extended Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Most physical systems are represented as continuous-time models while discrete-time measurements are made frequently for state estimation via a digital processor.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The prediction equations are derived from those of continuous-time Kalman filter without update from measurements, i.e., $\mathbf {K} (t)=0$ .
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The predicted state and covariance are calculated respectively by solving a set of differential equations with the initial value equal to the estimate at the previous step.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] For the case of linear time invariant systems, the continuous time dynamics can be exactly discretized into a discrete time system using matrix exponentials.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The update equations are identical to those of the discrete-time Kalman filter.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] The traditional Kalman filter has also been employed for the recovery of sparse, possibly dynamic, signals from noisy observations.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Recent works utilize notions from the theory of compressed sensing/sampling, such as the restricted isometry property and related probabilistic recovery arguments, for sequentially estimating the sparse state in intrinsically low-dimensional systems.
[src:control-systems/kalman-filter-p02] Since linear Gaussian state-space models lead to Gaussian processes, Kalman filters can be viewed as sequential solvers for Gaussian process regression.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A **proportional–integral–derivative** (**PID**) **controller**, or **three-term controller**, is a feedback-based control loop mechanism commonly used to manage machines and processes that require continuous control and automatic adjustment.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It is typically used in industrial control systems and various other applications where constant control through modulation is necessary without human intervention.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller automatically compares the desired target value (setpoint or SP) with the actual value of the system (process variable or PV).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The difference between these two values is called the *error value*, denoted as $e(t)$ .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It then applies corrective actions automatically to bring the PV to the same value as the SP using three methods: The proportional (*P*) component responds to the current error value by producing an output that is directly proportional to the magnitude of the error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This provides immediate correction based on how far the system is from the desired setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The integral (*I*) component, in turn, considers the cumulative sum of past errors to address any residual steady-state errors that persist over time, eliminating lingering discrepancies.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Lastly, the derivative (*D*) component predicts future error by assessing the rate of change of the error, which helps to mitigate overshoot and enhance system stability, particularly when the system undergoes rapid changes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID output signal can directly control actuators through voltage, current, or other modulation methods, depending on the application.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller reduces the likelihood of human error and improves automation.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A common example is a vehicle’s cruise control system.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] For instance, when a vehicle encounters a hill, its speed will decrease if the engine power output is kept constant.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller adjusts the engine's power output to restore the vehicle to its desired speed, doing so efficiently with minimal delay and overshoot.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The theoretical foundation of PID controllers dates back to the early 1920s with the development of automatic steering systems for ships.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This concept was later adopted for automatic process control in manufacturing, first appearing in pneumatic actuators and evolving into electronic controllers.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers are widely used in numerous applications requiring accurate, stable, and optimized automatic control, such as temperature regulation, motor speed control, and industrial process management.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The most distinguishing feature of the PID controller is the ability to use the three *control terms* of proportional, integral and derivative influence on the controller output to apply accurate and optimal control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The block diagram on the right shows the principles of how these terms are generated and applied.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It shows a PID controller, which continuously calculates an *error value* $e(t)$ as the difference between a desired setpoint ${\text{SP}}=r(t)$ and a measured process variable ${\text{PV}}=y(t)$ : $e(t)=r(t)-y(t)$ , and applies a correction based on proportional, integral, and derivative terms.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The controller attempts to minimize the error over time by adjustment of a *control variable* $u(t)$ , such as the opening of a control valve, to a new value determined by a weighted sum of the control terms.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller directly generates a continuous control signal based on error, without discrete modulation.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] where $K_{\text{p}}$ , $K_{\text{i}}$ , and $K_{\text{d}}$ , all non-negative, denote the coefficients for the proportional, integral, and derivative terms respectively (sometimes denoted *P*, *I*, and *D*).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Although a PID controller has three control terms, some applications need only one or two terms to provide appropriate control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This is achieved by setting the unused parameters to zero and is called a PI, PD, P, or I controller in the absence of the other control actions.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PI controllers are fairly common in applications where derivative action would be sensitive to measurement noise, but the integral term is often needed for the system to reach its target value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The use of the PID algorithm does not guarantee optimal control of the system or its control stability .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Situations may occur where there are excessive delays: the measurement of the process value is delayed, or the control action does not apply quickly enough.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In these cases, lead–lag compensation is required to be effective.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The response of the controller can be described in terms of its responsiveness to an error, the degree to which the system overshoots a setpoint, and the degree of any system oscillation.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] But the PID controller is broadly applicable since it relies only on the response of the measured process variable, not on knowledge or a model of the underlying process.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the 17th century to regulate the gap between millstones in windmills depending on the speed of rotation, and thereby compensate for the variable speed of grain feed.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] With the invention of the low-pressure stationary steam engine, there was a need for automatic speed control, and James Watt's self-designed "conical pendulum" governor, a set of revolving steel balls attached to a vertical spindle by link arms, came to be an industry standard.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This was based on the millstone-gap control concept.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Rotating-governor speed control, however, was still variable under conditions of varying load, where the shortcoming of what is now known as proportional control alone was evident.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The error between the desired speed and the actual speed would increase with increasing load.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In the 19th century, the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell in 1868 in his now-famous paper *On Governors*.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] He explored the mathematical basis for control stability and progressed a good way towards a solution, but made an appeal for mathematicians to examine the problem.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The problem was examined further in 1874 by Edward Routh, Charles Sturm, and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, all of whom contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In subsequent applications, speed governors were further refined, notably by American scientist Willard Gibbs, who in 1872 theoretically analyzed Watt's conical pendulum governor.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] About this time, the invention of the Whitehead torpedo posed a control problem that required accurate control of the running depth.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Use of a depth pressure sensor alone proved inadequate, and a pendulum that measured the fore and aft pitch of the torpedo was combined with depth measurement to become the pendulum-and-hydrostat control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Pressure control provided only a proportional control that, if the control gain was too high, would become unstable and go into overshoot with considerable instability of depth-holding.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The pendulum added what is now known as derivative control, which damped the oscillations by detecting the torpedo dive/climb angle and thereby the rate-of-change of depth.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This development (named by Whitehead as "The Secret" to give no clue to its action) was around 1868.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Another early example of a PID-type controller was developed by Elmer Sperry in 1911 for ship steering, though his work was intuitive rather than mathematically-based.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It was not until 1922, however, that a formal control law for what we now call PID or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Trials were carried out on the USS *New Mexico*, with the controllers controlling the *angular velocity* (not the angle) of the rudder.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PI control yielded sustained yaw (angular error) of ±2°.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Adding the D element yielded a yaw error of ±1/6°, better than most helmsmen could achieve.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The Navy ultimately did not adopt the system due to resistance by personnel.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Similar work was carried out and published by several others in the 1930s.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The wide use of feedback controllers did not become feasible until the development of wideband high-gain amplifiers to use the concept of negative feedback.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This had been developed in telephone engineering electronics by Harold Black in the late 1920s, but not published until 1934.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Independently, Clesson E Mason of the Foxboro Company in 1930 invented a wide-band pneumatic controller by combining the nozzle and flapper high-gain pneumatic amplifier, which had been invented in 1914, with negative feedback from the controller output.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This dramatically increased the linear range of operation of the nozzle and flapper amplifier, and integral control could also be added by the use of a precision bleed valve and a bellows generating the integral term.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The result was the "Stabilog" controller, which gave both proportional and integral functions using feedback bellows.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Later, the derivative term was added by a further bellows and adjustable orifice.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] From about 1932 onwards, the use of wideband pneumatic controllers increased rapidly in a variety of control applications.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Air pressure was used for generating the controller output, and also for powering process modulating devices such as diaphragm-operated control valves.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] They were simple low maintenance devices that operated well in harsh industrial environments and did not present explosion risks in hazardous locations.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] They were the industry standard for many decades until the advent of discrete electronic controllers and distributed control systems (DCSs).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] With these controllers, a pneumatic industry signaling standard of 3–15 psi (0.2–1.0 bar) was established, which had an elevated zero to ensure devices were working within their linear characteristic and represented the control range of 0-100%.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In the 1950s, when high-gain electronic amplifiers became cheap and reliable, electronic PID controllers became popular, and the pneumatic standard was emulated by 10-50 mA and 4–20 mA current loop signals (the latter became the industry standard).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Pneumatic field actuators are still widely used because of the advantages of pneumatic energy for control valves in process plant environments.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Most modern PID controls in industry are implemented as computer software in DCSs, programmable logic controllers (PLCs), or discrete compact controllers.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Electronic analog PID control loops were often found within more complex electronic systems, for example, the head positioning of a disk drive, the power conditioning of a power supply, or even the movement-detection circuit of a modern seismometer.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Discrete electronic analog controllers have been largely replaced by digital controllers using microcontrollers or FPGAs to implement PID algorithms.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] However, discrete analog PID controllers are still used in niche applications requiring high-bandwidth and low-noise performance, such as laser-diode controllers.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Consider a robotic arm that can be moved and positioned by a control loop.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] An electric motor may lift or lower the arm, depending on forward or reverse power applied, but power cannot be a simple function of position because of the inertial mass of the arm, forces due to gravity, external forces on the arm such as a load to lift or work to be done on an external object.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller continuously adjusts the input current to achieve smooth motion.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] By measuring the position (PV) and subtracting it from the setpoint (SP), the error (e) is found, and from it, the controller calculates how much electric current (MV) to supply to the motor.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The obvious method is **proportional** control: the motor current is set in proportion to the existing error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] However, this method fails if, for instance, the arm has to lift different weights: a greater weight needs a greater force applied for the same error on the down side, but a smaller force if the error is low on the upside.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] That's where the integral and derivative terms play their part.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] An **integral** term increases action in relation not only to the error but also the time for which it has persisted.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] So, if the applied force is not enough to bring the error to zero, this force will be increased as time passes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Applying too much integral when the error is small and decreasing will lead to overshoot.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] After overshooting, if the controller were to apply a large correction in the opposite direction and repeatedly overshoot the desired position, the output would oscillate around the setpoint in either a constant, growing, or decaying sinusoid.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the amplitude of the oscillations increases with time, the system is unstable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the oscillations remain at a constant magnitude, the system is marginally stable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A **derivative** term does not consider the magnitude of the error (meaning it cannot bring it to zero: a pure D controller cannot bring the system to its setpoint), but rather the rate of change of error, trying to bring this rate to zero.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It aims at flattening the error trajectory into a horizontal line, damping the force applied, and so reduces overshoot (error on the other side because of too great applied force).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In the interest of achieving a controlled arrival at the desired position (SP) in a timely and accurate way, the controlled system needs to be critically damped.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A well-tuned position control system will also apply the necessary currents to the controlled motor so that the arm pushes and pulls as necessary to resist external forces trying to move it away from the required position.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The setpoint itself may be generated by an external system, such as a PLC or other computer system, so that it continuously varies depending on the work that the robotic arm is expected to do.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A well-tuned PID control system will enable the arm to meet these changing requirements to the best of its capabilities.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If a controller starts from a stable state with zero error (PV = SP), then further changes by the controller will be in response to changes in other measured or unmeasured inputs to the process that affect the process, and hence the PV.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Variables that affect the process other than the MV are known as disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Generally, controllers are used to reject disturbances and to implement setpoint changes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A change in load on the arm constitutes a disturbance to the robot arm control process.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In theory, a controller can be used to control any process that has a measurable output (PV), a known ideal value for that output (SP), and an input to the process (MV) that will affect the relevant PV.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Controllers are used in industry to regulate temperature, pressure, force, feed rate, flow rate, chemical composition (component concentrations), weight, position, speed, and practically every other variable for which a measurement exists.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This section describes the parallel or non-interacting form of the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The PID control scheme is named after its three correcting terms, whose sum constitutes the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The proportional, integral, and derivative terms are summed to calculate the output of the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] where s is the complex angular frequency.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The proportional term produces an output value that is proportional to the current error value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The proportional response can be adjusted by multiplying the error by a constant *K*p, called the proportional gain constant.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A high proportional gain results in a large change in the output for a given change in the error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the proportional gain is too high, the system can become unstable (see the section on loop tuning).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In contrast, a small gain results in a small output response to a large input error, and a less responsive or less sensitive controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the proportional gain is too low, the control action may be too small when responding to system disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Tuning theory and industrial practice indicate that the proportional term should contribute the bulk of the output change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The **steady-state error** is the difference between the desired final output and the actual one.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Because a non-zero error is required to drive it, a proportional controller generally operates with a steady-state error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Steady-state error (SSE) is proportional to the process gain and inversely proportional to proportional gain.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] SSE may be mitigated by adding a compensating bias term to the setpoint AND output or corrected dynamically by adding an integral term.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The contribution from the integral term is proportional to both the magnitude of the error and the duration of the error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The integral in a PID controller is the sum of the instantaneous error over time and gives the accumulated offset that should have been corrected previously.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The accumulated error is then multiplied by the integral gain (*K*i) and added to the controller output.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The integral term accelerates the movement of the process towards setpoint and eliminates the residual steady-state error that occurs with a pure proportional controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] However, since the integral term responds to accumulated errors from the past, it can cause the present value to overshoot the setpoint value (see the section on loop tuning).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The derivative of the process error is calculated by determining the slope of the error over time and multiplying this rate of change by the derivative gain *K*d.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The magnitude of the contribution of the derivative term to the overall control action is termed the derivative gain, *K*d.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Derivative action predicts system behavior and thus improves settling time and stability of the system.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] An ideal derivative is not causal, so that implementations of PID controllers include an additional low-pass filtering for the derivative term to limit the high-frequency gain and noise.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Derivative action is seldom used in practice, though – by one estimate in only 25% of deployed controllers – because of its variable impact on system stability in real-world applications.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Even though there are only three parameters and it is simple to describe in principle, PID tuning is a difficult problem because it must satisfy complex criteria within the limitations of PID control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Accordingly, there are various methods for loop tuning, and more sophisticated techniques are the subject of patents; this section describes some traditional, manual methods for loop tuning.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Designing and tuning a PID controller appears to be conceptually intuitive, but can be hard in practice, if multiple (and often conflicting) objectives, such as short transient and high stability, are to be achieved.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers often provide acceptable control using default tunings, but performance can generally be improved by careful tuning, and performance may be unacceptable with poor tuning.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Usually, initial designs need to be adjusted repeatedly through computer simulations until the closed-loop system performs or compromises as desired.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Some processes have a degree of nonlinearity, so parameters that work well at full-load conditions do not work when the process is starting up from no load.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This can be corrected by gain scheduling (using different parameters in different operating regions).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the PID controller parameters (the gains of the proportional, integral and derivative terms) are chosen incorrectly, the controlled process input can be unstable; i.e., its output diverges, with or without oscillation, and is limited only by saturation or mechanical breakage.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Instability is caused by *excess* gain, particularly in the presence of significant lag.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Generally, stabilization of response is required and the process must not oscillate for any combination of process conditions and setpoints, though sometimes marginal stability (bounded oscillation) is acceptable or desired.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Mathematically, the origins of instability can be seen in the Laplace domain.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] where $K(s)$ is the PID transfer function, and $G(s)$ is the plant transfer function.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A system is *unstable* where the closed-loop transfer function diverges for some s .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This happens in situations where $K(s)G(s)=-1$ .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In other words, this happens when $|K(s)G(s)|=1$ with a 180° phase shift.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Stability is guaranteed when $K(s)G(s)<1$ for frequencies that suffer high phase shifts.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A more general formalism of this effect is known as the Nyquist stability criterion.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The optimal behavior on a process change or setpoint change varies depending on the application.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Two basic requirements are *regulation* (disturbance rejection – staying at a given setpoint) and *command tracking* (implementing setpoint changes).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] These terms refer to how well the controlled variable tracks the desired value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Specific criteria for command tracking include rise time and settling time.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Some processes must not allow an overshoot of the process variable beyond the setpoint if, for example, this would be unsafe.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Other processes must minimize the energy expended in reaching a new setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] There are several methods for tuning a PID loop.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The most effective methods generally involve developing some form of process model and then choosing P, I, and D based on the dynamic model parameters.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Manual tuning methods can be relatively time-consuming, particularly for systems with long loop times.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The choice of method depends largely on whether the loop can be taken offline for tuning, and on the response time of the system.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the system can be taken offline, the best tuning method often involves subjecting the system to a step change in input, measuring the output as a function of time, and using this response to determine the control parameters.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] If the system must remain online, one tuning method is to first set $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ values to zero.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Increase the $K_{p}$ until the output of the loop oscillates; then set $K_{p}$ to approximately half that value for a "quarter amplitude decay"-type response.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Then increase $K_{i}$ until any offset is corrected in sufficient time for the process, but not until too great a value causes instability.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Finally, increase $K_{d}$ , if required, until the loop is acceptably quick to reach its reference after a load disturbance.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Too much $K_{p}$ causes excessive response and overshoot.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Another heuristic tuning method is known as the Ziegler–Nichols method, introduced by John G.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] As in the method above, the $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ gains are first set to zero.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The oscillation frequency is often measured instead, and the reciprocals of each multiplication yields the same result.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] These gains apply to the ideal, parallel form of the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] When applied to the standard PID form, only the integral and derivative gains $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ are dependent on the oscillation period $T_{u}$ .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This method was developed in 1953 and is based on a first-order + time delay model.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Similar to the Ziegler–Nichols method, a set of tuning parameters were developed to yield a closed-loop response with a decay ratio of ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Arguably, the biggest problem with these parameters is that a small change in the process parameters could potentially cause a closed-loop system to become unstable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Published in 1984 by Karl Johan Åström and Tore Hägglund, the relay method temporarily operates the process using bang-bang control and measures the resultant oscillations.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The output is switched (as if by a relay, hence the name) between two values of the control variable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The values must be chosen so the process will cross the setpoint, but they need not be 0% and 100%; by choosing suitable values, dangerous oscillations can be avoided.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] As long as the process variable is below the setpoint, the control output is set to the higher value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] As soon as it rises above the setpoint, the control output is set to the lower value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Ideally, the output waveform is nearly square, spending equal time above and below the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The period and amplitude of the resultant oscillations are measured and used to compute the ultimate gain and period, which are then fed into the Ziegler–Nichols method.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Specifically, the ultimate period $T_{u}$ is assumed to be equal to the observed period, and the ultimate gain is computed as $K_{u}=4b/\pi a,$ where a is the amplitude of the process variable oscillation, and b is the amplitude of the control output change which caused it.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] There are numerous variants on the relay method.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] where *k*p is the process gain, *τ*p is the time constant, *θ* is the dead time, and *u*(*s*) is a step change input.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It is important when using this method to apply a large enough step-change input that the output can be measured; however, too large of a step change can affect the process stability.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Additionally, a larger step change ensures that the output does not change due to a disturbance (for best results, try to minimize disturbances when performing the step test).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] One way to determine the parameters for the first-order process is to use the 63.2% method.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In this method, the process gain (*k*p) is equal to the change in output divided by the change in input.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The dead time *θ* is the amount of time between when the step change occurred and when the output first changed.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The time constant (*τ*p) is the amount of time it takes for the output to reach 63.2% of the new steady-state value after the step change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] One downside to using this method is that it can take a while to reach a new steady-state value if the process has large time constants.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Most modern industrial facilities no longer tune loops using the manual calculation methods shown above.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Instead, PID tuning and loop optimization software are used to ensure consistent results.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] These software packages gather data, develop process models, and suggest optimal tuning.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Some software packages can even develop tuning by gathering data from reference changes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Mathematical PID loop tuning induces an impulse in the system and then uses the controlled system's frequency response to design the PID loop values.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In loops with response times of several minutes, mathematical loop tuning is recommended, because trial and error can take days just to find a stable set of loop values.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Some digital loop controllers offer a self-tuning feature in which very small setpoint changes are sent to the process, allowing the controller itself to calculate optimal tuning values.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Another approach calculates initial values via the Ziegler–Nichols method, and uses a numerical optimization technique to find better PID coefficients.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Other formulas are available to tune the loop according to different performance criteria.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Many patented formulas are now embedded within PID tuning software and hardware modules.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Advances in automated PID loop tuning software also deliver algorithms for tuning PID Loops in a dynamic or non-steady state (NSS) scenario.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The software models the dynamics of a process through a disturbance, and calculate PID control parameters in response.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] While PID controllers are applicable to many control problems and often perform satisfactorily without any improvements or only coarse tuning, they can perform poorly in some applications and do not, in general, provide *optimal* control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The fundamental difficulty with PID control is that it is a feedback control system with *constant* parameters and no direct knowledge of the process, and thus, overall performance is reactive and a compromise.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] While PID control is the best controller for an observer that has no model of the process, better performance can be obtained by overtly modeling the actor of the process without resorting to an observer.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers, when used alone, can give poor performance when the PID loop gains must be reduced so that the control system does not overshoot, oscillate or hunt about the control setpoint value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] They also have difficulties in the presence of non-linearities, may trade-off regulation versus response time, do not react to changing process behavior (say, the process changes after it has warmed up), and have lag in responding to large disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The most significant improvement is to incorporate feed-forward control with knowledge about the system, and using the PID only to control error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers work best when the loop to be controlled is linear and symmetric.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Thus, their performance in non-linear and asymmetric systems is degraded.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A nonlinear valve in a flow control application, for instance, will result in variable loop sensitivity that requires damping to prevent instability.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] One solution is to include a model of the valve's nonlinearity in the control algorithm to compensate for this.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] An asymmetric application, for example, is temperature control in HVAC systems that use only active heating (via a heating element), whereas only passive cooling is available.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Overshoot of rising temperature can only be corrected slowly; active cooling is not available to force temperature downward as a function of the control output.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In this case, the PID controller could be tuned to be over-damped, to prevent or reduce overshoot, but this reduces performance by increasing the settling time of a rising temperature to the set point.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] The inherent degradation of control quality in this application could be solved by application of active cooling.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A problem with the derivative term is that it amplifies higher frequency measurement or process noise that can cause large amounts of change in the output.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] It is often helpful to filter the measurements with a low-pass filter in order to remove higher-frequency noise components.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] As low-pass filtering and derivative control can cancel each other out, the amount of filtering is limited.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] Therefore, low-noise instrumentation can be important.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] A nonlinear median filter may be used, which improves the filtering efficiency and practical performance.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] In some cases, the differential band can be turned off with little loss of control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p01] This is equivalent to using the PID controller as a PI controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The basic PID algorithm presents some challenges in control applications that have been addressed by minor modifications to the PID form.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] One common problem resulting from the ideal PID implementations is integral windup.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Following a large change in setpoint, the integral term can accumulate an error larger than the maximal value for the regulation variable (windup), thus the system overshoots and continues to increase until this accumulated error is unwound.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] For example, a PID loop is used to control the temperature of an electric resistance furnace where the system has stabilized.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Now, when the door is opened and something cold is put into the furnace, the temperature drops below the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The integral function of the controller tends to compensate for error by introducing another error in the positive direction.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This overshoot can be avoided by freezing of the integral function after the opening of the door for the time the control loop typically needs to reheat the furnace.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] A **PI controller** (proportional–integral controller) is a special case of the PID controller in which the derivative (D) of the error is not used.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] where $\Delta$ is the error or deviation of actual measured value (***PV***) from the setpoint (***SP***).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Setting a value for G is often a trade off between decreasing overshoot and increasing settling time.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The lack of derivative action may make the system more steady in the steady state in the case of noisy data.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This is because derivative action is more sensitive to higher-frequency terms in the inputs.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Without derivative action, a PI-controlled system is less responsive to real (non-noise) and relatively fast alterations in state, and so the system will be slower to reach setpoint and slower to respond to perturbations than a well-tuned PID system may be.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Many PID loops control a mechanical device (for example, a valve).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Mechanical maintenance can be a major cost and wear leads to control degradation in the form of either stiction or backlash in the mechanical response to an input signal.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The rate of mechanical wear is mainly a function of how often a device is activated to make a change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Where wear is a significant concern, the PID loop may have an output deadband to reduce the frequency of activation of the output (valve).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This is accomplished by modifying the controller to hold its output steady if the change would be small (within the defined deadband range).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The calculated output must leave the deadband before the actual output will change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The proportional and derivative terms can produce excessive movement in the output when a system is subjected to an instantaneous step increase in the error, such as a large setpoint change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In the case of the derivative term, this is due to taking the derivative of the error, which is very large in the case of an instantaneous step change.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In this modification, the setpoint is gradually moved from its old value to a newly specified value using a linear or first-order differential ramp function.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In this case, the PID controller measures the derivative of the measured PV, rather than the derivative of the error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This quantity is always continuous (i.e., never has a step change as a result of changed setpoint).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This modification is a simple case of setpoint weighting.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Setpoint weighting adds adjustable factors (usually between 0 and 1) to the setpoint in the error in the proportional and derivative element of the controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The error in the integral term must be the true control error to avoid steady-state control errors.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] These two extra parameters do not affect the response to load disturbances and measurement noise and can be tuned to improve the controller's setpoint response.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The control system performance can be improved by combining the feedback (or closed-loop) control of a PID controller with feed-forward (or open-loop) control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Knowledge about the system (such as the desired acceleration and inertia) can be fed forward and combined with the PID output to improve the overall system performance.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The feed-forward value alone can often provide the major portion of the controller output.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The PID controller primarily has to compensate for whatever difference or *error* remains between the setpoint (SP) and the system response to the open-loop control.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Since the feed-forward output is not affected by the process feedback, it can never cause the control system to oscillate, thus improving the system response without affecting stability.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Feed forward can be based on the setpoint and on extra measured disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Setpoint weighting is a simple form of feed forward.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] For example, in most motion control systems, in order to accelerate a mechanical load under control, more force is required from the actuator.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] If a velocity loop PID controller is being used to control the speed of the load and command the force being applied by the actuator, then it is beneficial to take the desired instantaneous acceleration, scale that value appropriately and add it to the output of the PID velocity loop controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This means that whenever the load is being accelerated or decelerated, a proportional amount of force is commanded from the actuator regardless of the feedback value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The PID loop in this situation uses the feedback information to change the combined output to reduce the remaining difference between the process setpoint and the feedback value.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Working together, the combined open-loop feed-forward controller and closed-loop PID controller can provide a more responsive control system.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] PID controllers are often implemented with a "bumpless" initialization feature that recalculates the integral accumulator term to maintain a consistent process output through parameter changes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] A partial implementation is to store the integral gain times the error rather than storing the error and postmultiplying by the integral gain, which prevents discontinuous output when the I gain is changed, but not the P or D gains.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In addition to feed-forward, PID controllers are often enhanced through methods such as PID gain scheduling (changing parameters in different operating conditions), fuzzy logic, or computational verb logic.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Further practical application issues can arise from instrumentation connected to the controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] A high enough sampling rate, measurement precision, and measurement accuracy are required to achieve adequate control performance.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Another new method for improvement of PID controller is to increase the degree of freedom by using fractional order.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The order of the integrator and differentiator add increased flexibility to the controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] One distinctive advantage of PID controllers is that two PID controllers can be used together to yield better dynamic performance.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Two controllers are in cascade when they are arranged so that one regulates the set point of the other.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] A PID controller acts as outer loop controller, which controls the primary physical parameter, such as fluid level or velocity.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The other controller acts as inner loop controller, which reads the output of outer loop controller as setpoint, usually controlling a more rapid changing parameter, flowrate or acceleration.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] It can be mathematically proven that the working frequency of the controller is increased and the time constant of the object is reduced by using cascaded PID controllers..
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] For example, a temperature-controlled circulating bath has two PID controllers in cascade, each with its own thermocouple temperature sensor.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The outer controller controls the temperature of the water using a thermocouple located far from the heater, where it accurately reads the temperature of the bulk of the water.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The error term of this PID controller is the difference between the desired bath temperature and measured temperature.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Instead of controlling the heater directly, the outer PID controller sets a heater temperature goal for the inner PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The inner PID controller controls the temperature of the heater using a thermocouple attached to the heater.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The inner controller's error term is the difference between this heater temperature setpoint and the measured temperature of the heater.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Its output controls the actual heater to stay near this setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The proportional, integral, and differential terms of the two controllers will be very different.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The outer PID controller has a long time constant – all the water in the tank needs to heat up or cool down.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The inner loop responds much more quickly.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Each controller can be tuned to match the physics of the system *it* controls – heat transfer and thermal mass of the whole tank or of just the heater – giving better total response.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The form of the PID controller most often encountered in industry, and the one most relevant to tuning algorithms, is the *standard form*.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In this standard form, the parameters have a clear physical meaning.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In particular, the inner summation produces a new single error value, which is compensated for future and past errors.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The proportional error term is the current error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The derivative components term attempts to predict the error value at $T_{d}$ seconds (or samples) in the future, assuming that the loop control remains unchanged.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The integral component adjusts the error value to compensate for the sum of all past errors, with the intention of completely eliminating them in $T_{i}$ seconds (or samples).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The resulting compensated single error value is then scaled by the single gain $K_{p}$ to compute the control variable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] the gain parameters are related to the parameters of the standard form through $K_{i}=K_{p}/T_{i}$ and $K_{d}=K_{p}T_{d}$ .
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This parallel form, where the parameters are treated as simple gains, is the most general and flexible form.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] However, it is also the form where the parameters have the weakest relationship to physical behaviors and is generally reserved for theoretical treatment of the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The standard form, despite being slightly more complex mathematically, is more common in industry.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In many cases, the manipulated variable output by the PID controller is a dimensionless fraction between 0 and 100% of some maximum possible value, and the translation into real units (such as pumping rate or watts of heater power) is outside the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The process variable, however, is in dimensioned units such as temperature.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] It is common in this case to express the gain $K_{p}$ not as "output per degree", but rather in the reciprocal form of a *proportional band* $100/K_{p}$ , which is "degrees per full output": the range over which the output changes from 0 to 1 (0% to 100%).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Beyond this range, the output is saturated, full-off or full-on.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The narrower this band, the higher the proportional gain.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In most commercial control systems, derivative action is based on process variable rather than error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] That is, a change in the setpoint does not affect the derivative action.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This is because the digitized version of the algorithm produces a large unwanted spike when the setpoint is changed.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] If the setpoint is constant, then changes in the PV will be the same as changes in error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Therefore, this modification makes no difference to the way the controller responds to process disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Most commercial control systems offer the *option* of also basing the proportional action solely on the process variable.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This means that only the integral action responds to changes in the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The modification to the algorithm does not affect the way the controller responds to process disturbances.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Basing proportional action on PV eliminates the instant and possibly very large change in output caused by a sudden change to the setpoint.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Depending on the process and tuning, this may be beneficial to the response to a setpoint step.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] King describes an effective chart-based method.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Having the PID controller written in Laplace form and having the transfer function of the controlled system makes it easy to determine the closed-loop transfer function of the system.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This form essentially consists of a PD and PI controller in series.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] As the integral is required to calculate the controller's bias, this form provides the ability to track an external bias value, which is required to be used for proper implementation of multi-controller advanced control schemes.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The analysis for designing a digital implementation of a PID controller in a microcontroller (MCU) or FPGA device requires the standard form of the PID controller to be *discretized*.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Approximations for first-order derivatives are made by backward finite differences. $u(t)$ and $e(t)$ are discretized with a sampling period $\Delta t$ , k is the sample index.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] This constant is useful when you want to have a start and stop control on the regulation loop.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] For instance, setting Kp,Ki and Kd to 0 will keep u(t) constant.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Likewise, when you want to start a regulation on a system where the error is already close to 0 with u(t) non null, it prevents from sending the output to 0.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Here, `Kp` is a dimensionless number, `Ki` is expressed in s−1 and `Kd` is expressed in s.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] When doing a regulation where the actuator and the measured value are not in the same unit (e.g., temperature regulation using a motor controlling a valve), $K_{p}$ , $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ may be corrected by a unit conversion factor.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] It may also be interesting to use `Ki` in its reciprocal form (integration time).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The above implementation allows to perform an I-only controller which may be useful in some cases.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] In the real world, this is D-to-A converted and passed into the process under control as the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] The current error is stored elsewhere for re-use in the next differentiation, the program then waits until `dt` seconds have passed since start, and the loop begins again, reading in new values for the PV and the setpoint and calculating a new value for the error.
[src:control-systems/pid-controller-p02] Note that for real code, the use of `wait(dt)` might be inappropriate because it does not account for time taken by the algorithm itself during the loop, or more importantly, any pre-emption delaying the algorithm.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] In mechanical and control engineering, a **servomechanism** (also called **servo system**, or simply **servo**) is a control system for the position and its time derivatives, such as velocity, of a mechanical system.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] It often includes a servomotor, and uses closed-loop control to reduce steady-state error and improve dynamic response.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] In closed-loop control, error-sensing negative feedback is used to correct the action of the mechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] In displacement-controlled applications, it usually includes a built-in encoder or other position feedback mechanism to ensure the output is achieving the desired effect.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Following a specified motion trajectory is called **servoing**, where "servo" is used as a verb.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The *servo* prefix originates from the Latin word *servus* meaning 'slave'.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The term correctly applies only to systems where the feedback or error-correction signals help control mechanical position, speed, attitude or any other measurable variables.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] For example, an automotive power window control is not a servomechanism, as there is no automatic feedback that controls position—the operator does this by observation.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] By contrast a car's cruise control uses closed-loop feedback, which classifies it as a servomechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] A common type of servo provides *position control*.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Commonly, servos are electric, hydraulic, or pneumatic.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] They operate on the principle of negative feedback, where the control input is compared to the actual position of the mechanical system as measured by some type of transducer at the output.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Any positive or negative difference between the actual and wanted values (an "**error signal**") is amplified (and converted) and used to drive the system's motor in the direction necessary to reduce or eliminate the error, e.g. through an H-bridge controller.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] This procedure is one widely used application of control theory.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Typical servos can give a rotary (angular) or linear output.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Speed control via a governor is another type of servomechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The steam engine uses mechanical governors; another early application was to govern the speed of water wheels.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Prior to World War II the constant speed propeller was developed to control engine speed for maneuvering aircraft.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Fuel controls for gas turbine engines employ either hydromechanical or electronic governing.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Positioning servomechanisms were first used in military fire-control and marine navigation equipment.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Today servomechanisms are used in automatic machine tools, satellite-tracking antennas, remote control airplanes, automatic navigation systems on boats and planes, and antiaircraft-gun control systems.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Other examples are fly-by-wire systems in aircraft which use servos to actuate the aircraft's control surfaces, and radio-controlled models which use RC servos for the same purpose.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Many autofocus cameras also use a servomechanism to accurately move the lens.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] A hard disk drive has a magnetic servo system with sub-micrometer positioning accuracy.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] In industrial machines, servos are used to perform complex motion, in many applications.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] A *servomotor* is a specific type of motor that is combined with a rotary encoder or a potentiometer to form a servomechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] This assembly may in turn form part of another servomechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] A potentiometer provides a simple analog signal to indicate position, while an encoder provides position and usually speed feedback, which by the use of a PID controller allow more precise control of position and thus faster achievement of a stable position (for a given motor power).
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Potentiometers are subject to drift when the temperature changes whereas encoders are more stable and accurate.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Servomotors are used for both high-end and low-end applications.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] On the high end are precision industrial components that use a rotary encoder.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] On the low end are inexpensive radio control servos (RC servos) used in radio-controlled models which use a free-running motor and a simple potentiometer position sensor with an embedded controller.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The term *servomotor* generally refers to a high-end industrial component while the term *servo* is most often used to describe the inexpensive devices that employ a potentiometer.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Stepper motors are not considered to be servomotors, although they too are used to construct larger servomechanisms.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Stepper motors have inherent angular positioning, owing to their construction, and this is generally used in an open-loop manner without feedback.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] They are generally used for medium-precision applications.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] RC servos are used to provide actuation for various mechanical systems such as the steering of a car, the control surfaces on a plane, or the rudder of a boat.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Due to their affordability, reliability, and simplicity of control by microprocessors, they are often used in small-scale robotics applications.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] A standard RC receiver (or a microcontroller) sends pulse-width modulation (PWM) signals to the servo.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The electronics inside the servo translate the width of the pulse into a position.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] When the servo is commanded to rotate, the motor is powered until the potentiometer reaches the value corresponding to the commanded position.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] James Watt's steam engine governor is generally considered the first powered feedback system.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The windmill fantail is an earlier example of automatic control, but since it does not have an amplifier or gain, it is not usually considered a servomechanism.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The first feedback position control device was the ship steering engine, used to position the rudder of large ships based on the position of the ship's wheel.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] His patented design was used on the SS Great Eastern in 1866.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Joseph Farcot may deserve equal credit for the feedback concept, with several patents between 1862 and 1868.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The telemotor was invented around 1872 by Andrew Betts Brown, allowing elaborate mechanisms between the control room and the engine to be greatly simplified.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Steam steering engines had the characteristics of a modern servomechanism: an input, an output, an error signal, and a means for amplifying the error signal used for negative feedback to drive the error towards zero.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The Ragonnet power reverse mechanism was a general purpose air or steam-powered servo amplifier for linear motion patented in 1909.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms were used as early as 1888 in Elisha Gray's Telautograph.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Electrical servomechanisms require a power amplifier.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] World War II saw the development of electrical fire-control servomechanisms, using an amplidyne as the power amplifier.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Vacuum tube amplifiers were used in the UNISERVO tape drive for the UNIVAC I computer.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The Royal Navy began experimenting with Remote Power Control (RPC) on HMS Champion in 1928 and began using RPC to control searchlights in the early 1930s.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] During WW2 RPC was used to control gun mounts and gun directors.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Modern servomechanisms use solid state power amplifiers, usually built from MOSFET or thyristor devices.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The origin of the word is believed to come from the French "*Le Servomoteur*" or the slavemotor, first used by J.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] Farcot in 1868 to describe hydraulic and steam engines for use in ship steering.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The simplest kind of servos use bang–bang control.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] More complex control systems use proportional control, PID control, and state space control, which are studied in modern control theory.
[src:control-systems/servomechanism] The servo bandwidth indicates the capability of the servo to follow rapid changes in the commanded input.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] In cybernetics and control theory, a **setpoint** (**SP**; also **set point**) is the desired or target value for an essential variable, or process value (PV) of a control system, which may differ from the actual measured value of the variable.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] Departure of such a variable from its setpoint is one basis for error-controlled regulation using negative feedback for automatic control.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] A setpoint can be any physical quantity or parameter that a control system seeks to regulate, such as temperature, pressure, flow rate, position, speed, or any other measurable attribute.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] In the context of PID controller, the setpoint represents the reference or goal for the controlled process variable.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] It serves as the benchmark against which the actual process variable (PV) is continuously compared.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] The PID controller calculates an error signal by taking the difference between the setpoint and the current value of the process variable.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] where $e(t)$ is the error at a given time t , $SP$ is the setpoint, $PV(t)$ is the process variable at time t .
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] The PID controller uses this error signal to determine how to adjust the control output to bring the process variable as close as possible to the setpoint while maintaining stability and minimizing overshoot.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] The $SP-PV$ error can be used to return a system to its norm.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as gradients cause speed changes (PV), and the driver also alters the desired set speed (SP).
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] The automatic control algorithm restores the actual speed to the desired speed in the optimum way, without delay or overshoot, by altering the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] In this way the $SP-PV$ error is used to control the PV so that it equals the SP.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] A widespread of $SP-PV$ error is classically used in the PID controller.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] Special consideration must be given for engineering applications.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] In industrial systems, physical or process restraints may limit the determined set point.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] For example, a reactor which operates more efficiently at higher temperatures may be rated to withstand 500°C.
[src:control-systems/setpoint-control-system] However, for safety reasons, the set point for the reactor temperature control loop would be well below this limit, even if this means the reactor is running less efficiently.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In control engineering and system identification, a **state-space representation** is a mathematical model of a physical system that uses state variables to track how inputs shape system behavior over time through first-order differential equations or difference equations.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] These state variables change based on their current values and inputs, while outputs depend on the states and sometimes the inputs too.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The **state space** (also called **time-domain approach** and equivalent to phase space in certain dynamical systems) is a geometric space where the axes are these state variables, and the system’s state is represented by a state vector.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] For linear, time-invariant, and finite-dimensional systems, the equations can be written in matrix form, offering a compact alternative to the frequency domain’s Laplace transforms for multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Unlike the frequency domain approach, it works for systems beyond just linear ones with zero initial conditions.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This approach turns systems theory into an algebraic framework, making it possible to use Kronecker structures for efficient analysis.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] State-space models are applied in fields such as economics, statistics, computer science, electrical engineering, and neuroscience.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In econometrics, for example, state-space models can be used to decompose a time series into trend and cycle, compose individual indicators into a composite index, identify turning points of the business cycle, and estimate GDP using latent and unobserved time series.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Many applications rely on the Kalman Filter or a state observer to produce estimates of the current unknown state variables using their previous observations.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The internal state variables are the smallest possible subset of system variables that can represent the entire state of the system at any given time.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The minimum number of state variables required to represent a given system, n , is usually equal to the order of the system's defining differential equation, but not necessarily.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] If the system is represented in transfer function form, the minimum number of state variables is equal to the order of the transfer function's denominator after it has been reduced to a proper fraction.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] It is important to understand that converting a state-space realization to a transfer function form may lose some internal information about the system, and may provide a description of a system which is stable, when the state-space realization is unstable at certain points.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In electric circuits, the number of state variables is often, though not always, the same as the number of energy storage elements in the circuit such as capacitors and inductors.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The state variables defined must be linearly independent, i.e., no state variable can be written as a linear combination of the other state variables.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In this general formulation, all matrices are allowed to be time-variant (i.e. their elements can depend on time); however, in the common LTI case, matrices will be time invariant.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The time variable t can be continuous (e.g. $t\in \mathbb {R}$ ) or discrete (e.g. $t\in \mathbb {Z}$ ).
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In the latter case, the time variable k is usually used instead of t .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Hybrid systems allow for time domains that have both continuous and discrete parts.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Stability and natural response characteristics of a continuous-time LTI system (i.e., linear with matrices that are constant with respect to time) can be studied from the eigenvalues of the matrix $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The stability of a time-invariant state-space model can be determined by looking at the system's transfer function in factored form.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] These poles can be used to analyze whether the system is asymptotically stable or marginally stable.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] An alternative approach to determining stability, which does not involve calculating eigenvalues, is to analyze the system's Lyapunov stability.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The zeros found in the numerator of $\mathbf {G} (s)$ can similarly be used to determine whether the system is minimum phase.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The system may still be **input–output stable** (see BIBO stable) even though it is not internally stable.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This may be the case if unstable poles are canceled out by zeros (i.e., if those singularities in the transfer function are removable).
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The state controllability condition implies that it is possible – by admissible inputs – to steer the states from any initial value to any final value within some finite time window.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Observability is a measure for how well internal states of a system can be inferred by knowledge of its external outputs.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Assuming zero initial conditions $\mathbf {x} (0)=\mathbf {0}$ and a single-input single-output (SISO) system, the transfer function is defined as the ratio of output and input $G(s)=Y(s)/U(s)$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] For a multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) system, however, this ratio is not defined.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Consequently, $\mathbf {G} (s)$ is a matrix with the dimension $q\times p$ which contains transfer functions for each input output combination.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Due to the simplicity of this matrix notation, the state-space representation is commonly used for multiple-input, multiple-output systems.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The Rosenbrock system matrix provides a bridge between the state-space representation and its transfer function.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Given a transfer function, expand it to reveal all coefficients in both the numerator and denominator.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This state-space realization is called **controllable canonical form** because the resulting model is guaranteed to be controllable (i.e., because the control enters a chain of integrators, it has the ability to move every state).
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This state-space realization is called **observable canonical form** because the resulting model is guaranteed to be observable (i.e., because the output exits from a chain of integrators, every state has an effect on the output).
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Transfer functions which are only proper (and not strictly proper) can also be realised quite easily.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The strictly proper transfer function can then be transformed into a canonical state-space realization using techniques shown above.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The state-space realization of the constant is trivially $\mathbf {y} (t)=\mathbf {G} (\infty )\mathbf {u} (t)$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Together we then get a state-space realization with matrices *A*, *B* and *C* determined by the strictly proper part, and matrix *D* determined by the constant.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This is due to the $\mathbf {G} (\infty )$ constant in the transfer function.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] A common method for feedback is to multiply the output by a matrix *K* and setting this as the input to the system: $\mathbf {u} (t)=K\mathbf {y} (t)$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Since the values of *K* are unrestricted the values can easily be negated for negative feedback.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The presence of a negative sign (the common notation) is merely a notational one and its absence has no impact on the end results.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The advantage of this is that the eigenvalues of *A* can be controlled by setting *K* appropriately through eigendecomposition of $\left(A+BK\left(I-DK\right)^{-1}C\right)$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This assumes that the closed-loop system is controllable or that the unstable eigenvalues of *A* can be made stable through appropriate choice of *K*.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] For a strictly proper system *D* equals zero.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Another fairly common situation is when all states are outputs, i.e.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] *y* = *x*, which yields *C* = *I*, the identity matrix.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This reduces the necessary eigendecomposition to just $A+BK$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] In addition to feedback, an input, $r(t)$ , can be added such that $\mathbf {u} (t)=-K\mathbf {y} (t)+\mathbf {r} (t)$ .
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] A classical linear system is that of one-dimensional movement of an object (e.g., a cart).
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] This means, that if initial state of the system is known ( $y(t)$ , ${\dot {y}}(t)$ , ${\ddot {y}}(t)$ ), and if the b and m are constants, then there is a force u that could move the cart into any other position in the system.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] Therefore, this system is both controllable and observable.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The more general form of a state-space model can be written as two functions.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The first is the state equation and the latter is the output equation.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] If the function $f(\cdot ,\cdot ,\cdot )$ is a linear combination of states and inputs then the equations can be written in matrix notation like above.
[src:control-systems/state-space-representation] The $u(t)$ argument to the functions can be dropped if the system is unforced (i.e., it has no inputs).
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In engineering, a **transfer function** (also known as **system function** or **network function**) of a system, sub-system, or component is a mathematical function that models the system's output for each possible input.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] It is widely used in electronic engineering tools like circuit simulators and control systems and in chemical reaction engineering for the study and modeling of the residence time distribution and stability of a reactor.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In simple cases, this function can be represented as a two-dimensional graph of an independent scalar input versus the dependent scalar output (known as a **transfer curve** or **characteristic curve**).
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Transfer functions for components are used to design and analyze systems assembled from components, particularly using the block diagram technique, in electronics and control theory.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Dimensions and units of the transfer function model the output response of the device for a range of possible inputs.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The term *transfer function* is also used in the frequency domain analysis of systems using transform methods, such as the Laplace transform; it is the amplitude of the output as a function of the frequency of the input signal.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The transfer function of an electronic filter is the amplitude at the output as a function of the frequency of a constant amplitude sine wave applied to the input.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] For optical imaging devices, the optical transfer function is the Fourier transform of the point spread function (a function of spatial frequency).
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Transfer functions are commonly used in the analysis of systems such as single-input single-output filters in signal processing, communication theory, and control theory.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The term is often used exclusively to refer to linear time-invariant (LTI) systems.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Most real systems have non-linear input–output characteristics, but many systems operated within nominal parameters (not over-driven) have behavior close enough to linear that LTI system theory is an acceptable representation of their input–output behavior.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Descriptions are given in terms of a complex variable, $s=\sigma +j\cdot \omega$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In many applications it is sufficient to set $\sigma =0$ (thus $s=j\cdot \omega$ ), which reduces the Laplace transforms with complex arguments to Fourier transforms with the real argument ω.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] This is common in applications primarily interested in the LTI system's steady-state response (often the case in signal processing and communication theory), not the fleeting turn-on and turn-off transient response or stability issues.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Discrete-time signals may be notated as arrays indexed by an integer n (e.g. $x[n]$ for input and $y[n]$ for output).
