[src:control-systems/transfer-function] That kind of equation can be used to constrain the output function *u* in terms of the *forcing* function *r*.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The transfer function can be used to define an operator $F[r]=u$ that serves as a right inverse of *L*, meaning that $L[F[r]]=r$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Solutions of the homogeneous constant-coefficient differential equation $L[u]=0$ can be found by trying $u=e^{\lambda t}$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The inhomogeneous case can be easily solved if the input function *r* is also of the form $r(t)=e^{st}$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] A general sinusoidal input to a system of frequency $\omega _{0}/(2\pi )$ may be written $\exp(j\omega _{0}t)$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The response of a system to a sinusoidal input beginning at time $t=0$ will consist of the sum of the steady-state response and a transient response.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The steady-state response is the output of the system in the limit of infinite time, and the transient response is the difference between the response and the steady-state response; it corresponds to the homogeneous solution of the differential equation.
