[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In a linear time-invariant system, the input frequency $\omega$ has not changed; only the amplitude and phase angle of the sinusoid have been changed by the system.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The transfer function can also be shown using the Fourier transform, a special case of bilateral Laplace transform where $s=j\omega$ .
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In control engineering and control theory, the transfer function is derived with the Laplace transform.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] The transfer function was the primary tool used in classical control engineering.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] A transfer matrix can be obtained for any linear system to analyze its dynamics and other properties; each element of a transfer matrix is a transfer function relating a particular input variable to an output variable.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] A representation bridging state space and transfer function methods was proposed by Howard H.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Rosenbrock, and is known as the Rosenbrock system matrix.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] In imaging, transfer functions are used to describe the relationship between the scene light, the image signal and the displayed light.
[src:control-systems/transfer-function] Transfer functions do not exist for many non-linear systems, such as relaxation oscillators; however, describing functions can sometimes be used to approximate such nonlinear time-invariant systems.
